# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: african-buffalo
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] In the 1890s, an epizootic of the rinderpest virus struck all across Africa, but primarily in Eastern and Southern Africa.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] It was considered to be "the most devastating epidemic to hit southern Africa in the late nineteenth century." It killed more than 5.2 million cattle south of the Zambezi, as well as domestic oxen, sheep, and goats, and wild populations of buffalo, giraffe, and wildebeest.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] The effects of the outbreak were drastic, leading to massive famine, economic collapse, and disease outbreak in humans.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] Starvation spread across the region, resulting in the death of an estimated third of the human population of Ethiopia and two-thirds of the Maasai people of Tanzania.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] The famine and the massive decrease in cattle population led to a change in the landscape from grass to thornbush.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] This formed the ideal habitat for tsetse fly and allowed them to expand from central and western Africa to the rest of the continent.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] Tsetse fly carry the parasite that causes the deadly African sleeping sickness.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] This disease, which affects both humans and animals, further exacerbated the economic and social effects of rinderpest on Africans.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] The Rinderpest epizootic facilitated further colonial conquest by creating famine, economic dislocation, and landscape transformations.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] Rinderpest had been common in Europe before the European colonisation of Africa.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] Despite the familiarity of Rinderpest to Europeans, it had ceased to be a problem in many countries, such as Germany, thanks to modern veterinary policing and cross-border regulation of the cattle trade.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] Rinderpest was introduced to parts of Africa by infected cattle imported from Asia to feed Italian forces during the Italo-Ethiopian War of 1887–1889.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] However, the disease did not cross the Sahara until the 1880s; its spread was rapid, trickling in from inland regions during German military campaigns of the 1880s and 1890s.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] Rinderpest was referred to as *sadoka* in East Africa.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] Evidence of the disease in Eritrean and Ethiopian cattle existed almost a decade before the epizootic in Southern Africa.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] The Emperor of Ethiopia was said to have lost over 250,000 cattle.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] In addition, a serious outbreak of rinderpest had been reported in Bombay in 1882.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] A popular Ethiopian tradition asserts that their cattle was deliberately inoculated with rinderpest by the Italians as during the Italo-Ethiopian War.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] It spread throughout the Horn of Africa, and crossed the Zambezi in March 1896.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] Colonial officials in German East Africa along with other Europeans originally identified *sadoka* as a disease unique to rinderpest, and argued that it was spread by Africans.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] Many Africans believed the disease was a product of European colonisation.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] Rinderpest was able to spread efficiently from the northeast to the south of Africa due to beneficial environmental conditions.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] The virus was spread though close contact at water sources such as watering holes and rivers where cattle and other mammals would gather.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] Local wild buffalo played a key role in the infection of the cattle of the Maasai people.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] In three years, rinderpest travelled 8000 km from the Southern Sahel Massawa, Eritrea to Dakar in West Africa although it took another year to travel south to the Zambezi before it infected groups in Bulawayo in modern Zimbabwe.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] In addition, Africa experienced a series of unfortunately timed meteorological El Niño-Southern Oscillation (ENSO) events between late 1880s to the early 1890s.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] This caused major droughts throughout the continent from the horn of Africa down to south Africa which caused massive concentrations of populations to gather at water sources.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] This encouraged the spread of the virus as it allowed large numbers to get infected quickly in a short amount of time.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] Frederick Lugard, the future Governor-General of Nigeria, stated: "Never before in the memory of man, or by the voice of tradition, have the cattle died in such vast numbers; never before has the wild game suffered.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] The rinderpest epizootic first swept through the coastal region of Eritrea in 1887.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] The disease swept across the northern provinces of Tigray and Shewa southwards, resulting in an estimated 90% mortality of the country's cattle population and wildlife, including buffaloes and antelopes.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] From there, it then reached through the Borena Zone of Southern Ethiopia in 18–30 days, Central Ethiopia in 8 days and Eritrea in 3 days.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] The severity of the rinderpest was influenced by which animals the communities depended on.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] As it left behind little to no cattle, communities such as the Maasai were hit hard while the Somali people and Gabra were almost untouched as they relied on camels.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] The Borana people in Southern Ethiopia used a pastoral economy reliant on cows when the rinderpest arrived in August 1891.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] Cattle played an important role in marriages, as a food source, and in the maintenance of social security networks.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] As a result, the Borana was left without an economy and food.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] The only ones who managed to keep their herds alive were those who were already in remote areas.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] The ones who were hit the hardest were those relying on the Tula wells for water, as these became centres where infection spread.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] As the disease travelled, the wells and grazing land surrounding them were abandoned in fear of infection.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] Additional problems arose as the rinderpest also killed animals such as buffalo, Grant’s gazelle, and giraffes, meaning that predators like lions and hyenas had fewer alternatives when hunting.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] This led to increased predation of humans who were already weak from famine and smallpox outbreaks by these animals.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] In Northern Ethiopia, hyenas were particularly dangerous, and often dragged people out of their homes during the night.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] Hyenas often also dug up and consumed decaying human flesh.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] Rinderpest primarily increased the disease burden among the Borana.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] For example, many people who ate the meat from rinderpest-riddled cattle often died of diarrhoea, probably as a result of the unsanitary condition of the meat.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] In the late 1880s, the region was also experiencing a smallpox epidemic.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] Smallpox was exacerbated as the mass migration of people attempting to avoid the rinderpest outbreak led to increased infection.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] Whole families died out as a result of the epizootic.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] The rinderpest epidemic also caused a restructure of Borana society.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] The survivors of the epizootic organized themselves into larger settlements around the wells, both to keep the wells open and functional but also as a precaution against predators.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] In addition, in response to the famine, customary rules and taboos around food had been abolished.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] Community chiefs enacted policies that declared all rules and taboos to be forgiven, and strict laws were enacted to prevent further "rule breaking." Europeans travelling through the area, like H.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] Cavendish, made remarks on the prosperity of the land only a handful of years after the Rinderpest swept through the area.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] In modern times, the Borana uses term the *ciinna*, meaning ”termination of everything”, for the overall impact the pest had on the society.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] In addition to Eastern and Southern Africa, rinderpest also spread across West Africa and decimated the cattle of the Hausa-Fulani people.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] 80–90% of all the cattle of the Fulani died.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] Rinderpest is believed to have arrived in the Ouaddaï Region by 1891, and Parfait-Louis Monteil's expedition into West Africa encountered "cattle plague" in what is now Dori, Burkina Faso in April of 1891.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] In French West Africa and German Cameroon, 98% of all the cattle in the region had died.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] In Hausa, the epizootic was referred to as "sannu," from an Hausa greeting of sympathy.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] The devastating loss of cattle of the Fulani is said to have driven many of the Fulani insane, where Fulani cattle owners were said to have left their families and wandered unclothed, looking for their dead cattle.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] The disease had a long-effect on the nomadic lifestyle and economy of the Fulani.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] It returned and killed cattle during the years 1913–14 and 1919–20.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] As late as 1944, the Fulani believed that their new cattle, which they had obtained by buying expensive unborn calves, were inferior to the cattle of the pre-rinderpest time.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] Germans were ignorant of the extent and complexity of many human and livestock diseases in Africa, including rinderpest.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] In Tanzania, rinderpest was associated with massive wildlife mortality, which often accompanied or preceded the death of cattle by rinderpest.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] This further caused the disease to go largely unnoticed, as rinderpest was not associated with wildlife mortality by the Germans.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] Despite the massive amount of cattle death among the Maasai, the epizootic was only shown concern by the Germans when the livestock around ports and military stations began to die.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] The German response to rinderpest often included border controls, as well as preventative slaughtering of otherwise healthy cattle, increasing dissatisfaction and anger among the local population.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] Among the Maasai people, who were primarily pastoral cattle herders, rinderpest contributed to mass famine, and often forced them to rely on outside ethnic polities that practice agriculture, like the Wayambo.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] The virus damaged various areas of society for pastoralists in Southern Bechuanaland (modern-day Botswana), as cattle was crucial to their survival.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] They relied on their livestock as their only source of income and cattle were a large percent of the colonial economy.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] Moreover, Southern Bechuanaland was a very dry region, which meant there was a lack of water sources that farmers could use.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] Thus, farmers were forced to take their livestock to the select few water holes in their areas which meant they were mixing with the infected wild mammals.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] The Bechuanaland colonial government did not collaborate with the Tswanas and Boers in managing the disease, leading to further spread of the disease across the region.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] Similarly in Cape Colony, particularly in the Eastern Cape, oxen were both crucial to the agrarian systems.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] A declining population of the cattle caused by rinderpest caused massive famine and starvation.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] As a result of this, many communities turned to skinning and dried out the meat of the large number of carcasses to preserve them; however, this was only a temporary solution to famine.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] The loss of cattle because of rinderpest also affected other aspects of life across Africa.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] Cow manure was a useful material that was used in various ways in African countries, including to plaster walls and floors, and also as a natural fertilizer on the land.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] The loss of cattle further affect agriculture by forcing farmers to find an alternative to manure and farm in new ways to bring yield.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] Disease epidemics had afflicted both humans and livestock for many decades before the rinderpest epizootic.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] Between 1860-1895, the Natal and Zululand regions had suffered from drought and stock disease.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] White traders introduced Contagious bovine pleuropneumonia, which by 1872 had killed 50% of all the cattle in the Zulu Kingdom.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] Horse sickness had killed a large portion the equine population, and Bluetongue disease killed most of the sheep between the 1860s to 1870s.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] Thus, the introduction of rinderpest devastated the already weakened agricultural systems and economies of southern Africa.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] This primarily affected transport riders, who were engaged in the haulage of goods by ox-wagon between gold mines in the Natal and Witwatersrand gold fields.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] This also led to the killing of tends of thousands of transport oxen who were killed as a way of stamping-out rinderpest, which brought heavy losses to Natal's ox-drawn transport system.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] This primarily affected black peasants in the region.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] Rinderpest impoverished many hundreds of black peasant tenants and caused them to either be driven off the land or made them more indebted to white landlords.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] This was seen as beneficial for many colonialists, who saw this as a way to move Africans away from traditional methods of farming and cattle herding to developing habits of industry and waged labor.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] In Southern Africa, rinderpest seemed to have even benefited white settlers.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] While both whites and blacks lost cattle, in 1896 black farmers owned 494,402 and by 1898, they owned 75,842.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] It took more than 8 years for black farmers to recoup their losses.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] The South African farming sector had also been weakened prior to rinderpest due to an infestation of red locusts in 1895 and 1896.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] Large swarms of locusts migrated from the northeast to the south coastal area of KwaZulu-Natal in August 1895.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] They caused massive amounts of damage to whole mealies and sugar cane fields.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] This resulted in major loss for farmers who invested in their field but were left with no crops to sell as due to extreme damage.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] The rinderpest epidemic seriously disrupted the socio-economic norms of the Nguni societies, who had evolved around cattle as a source of wealth.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] It not only eradicated many chief's sources of storable wealth, it threw their entire social system into disarray.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] Marriage was even thrown into disarray, as cattle were used to meet the commitments of bridewealth (ilobola) that was to be given to prospective fathers-in-law.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] Thus, marriages were postponed, and the system of loaning cattle to the poor, or ukusisa, was also abolished.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] As a result of the rinderpest epizootic, cattle disappeared across Eastern Africa.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] As a result, many forms of wild organisms reclaimed these former cattle pastures, including tsetse fly.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] In addition, former cattle herders who, having lost their economic livelihoods, turned to hunting, which forced them to encroach into bush areas with increased populations of tsetse fly.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] Sleeping sickness, a parasitic disease transmitted by tsetse fly, was endemic to Africa and outbreaks of the disease had been documented for many centuries, for example, the Malian king, Mari Djata II of Mali, is reported to have died of it in the 14 century.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] As a result of bites from tsetse fly, thousands of Africans contracted sleeping sickness.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] Between the years of 1900–1904, 200,000 out of the 300,000 inhabitants of the infected regions of Eastern and Southern Africa died of sleeping sickness.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] Another reason for the spread of African sleeping sickness via the rinderpest epizootic was the severe impact the epizootic had on agriculture.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] Farmers abandoning their fields caused them to revert to bush, which was the preferred habitat of tsetse flies.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] This primarily also led to an outbreak of sleeping sickness in Tanganyika during World War I.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] In addition, the rebound of wildlife killed by rinderpest often increased the amount of tsetse flies, and thus increased fatalities of sleeping sickness.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] Throughout Africa, the colonial governments had different responses to the rinderpest epizootic.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] In Southern Africa, white farmers seem to have benefited from the epizootic, it forced more black peasants off the land and into wage labor, and many White farmers were able to reap high profits by selling stocks to Africans who needed rinderpest free cattle.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] The average price of "salted" or rinderpest-free cattle quadrupled in price between 1895 and 1905.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] Many governments like the government of the Colony of Natal enacted mandatory quarantines and halted the movement of cows.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] Movement was often crucial to the cattle-based societies of the Nguni and Maasai people, and thus, these "erratic" quarantines often did little to prevent the spread of the epidemic, but maximized the societal collapse of these people.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] In many ways, colonial governments ignored the spread of rinderpest.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] Among the Borana people, the few domesticated animals to survive in Borana areas were donkeys and horses.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] Across Africa, equine mammals were important in helping communities start rebuilding themselves.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] Horses, in combination with dogs, were used to aid in hunting of game, while donkeys were used as pack animals and helped restart trade and social networks.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] The response of many of the European colonial governments in Africa to the spread of rinderpest was the preventative slaughter of healthy cattle, often to protect European livestock.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] This angered many native Africans, which was exacerbated by the fact that cattle killed by Europeans were burned and buried, while dead cattle was often consumed in times of famine.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] The devastating impact of the loss of cattle instigated more conflict between local Africans and European settlers.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] In Southern Africa, Galeshiwe, the chief of the Batlhaping tribe, declared that "he would never permit his cattle to be shot." This later led to the Langeberg Rebellion (1896–97).
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] There were few veterinarians on the ground to identify the disease, and observations of wildlife mortality, which was not considered a characteristic of European rinderpest, confused diagnoses.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] Despite attempts at veterinary policy, like the Cape Animal Diseases Act, most veterinary policy failed at halting the epidemic.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] This, along with the fact that it was feared Africans would uprise in mass against colonial governments, encouraged the development of a rinderpest vaccination.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] The South African Republic and German government, largely in southern and eastern Africa, worked to find an effective vaccine.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] By 1897, vaccine therapies succeeded in limiting rinderpest mortality to less than 20% in the Cape Colony.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] However, rinderpest remained an unsolved and ongoing problem in other parts of Africa throughout the 20th century, and became enzootic in most of Africa.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] Outbreaks also continued to be present in Korea, Japan, China, and the Philippines.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] By the 1960s, the International Rinderpest Joint Project (JP-15) campaign came close to eradicating rinderpest from Africa.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] It continued to have high mortality in animals like the Lesser kudu, giraffes, and warthogs.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] Famine and civil unrest caused by political violence halted the eradication and led to future epizootics throughout the 1980s, primarily in the Horn of Africa.
[src:african-buffalo/1890s-african-rinderpest-epizootic] Rinderpest was declared eradicated on May 25, 2011.
[src:african-buffalo/abbott-s-duiker] Abbott's duikers stand around 65 cm (26 in) tall at the shoulder and weigh about 55 kg (121 lb).
[src:african-buffalo/abbott-s-duiker] This duiker has a glossy, dark brown coat which is lighter on the underside.
[src:african-buffalo/abbott-s-duiker] The face is paler and grey in colour, with a large red tuft on the forehead; the horns are thin and short (8 to 12 cm (3.1 to 4.7 in)).
[src:african-buffalo/abbott-s-duiker] The secretive behaviour of Abbott's duiker, along with its largely nocturnal habits and preference for dense vegetation, means little is known about the ecology and behaviour of this species.
[src:african-buffalo/abbott-s-duiker] It has been observed feeding on leaves in the forest understory, and on vegetation in forest clearings, and may feed on fruits, flowers and moss.
[src:african-buffalo/abbott-s-duiker] An Abbott's duiker has also been seen with a frog in its mouth; duikers are known to capture and feed on live prey occasionally.
[src:african-buffalo/abbott-s-duiker] The cryptic habits and alertness of Abbott's duiker unfortunately does not protect it entirely from predation.
[src:african-buffalo/abbott-s-duiker] Young Abbott's duikers are probably preyed on by African crowned eagles (*Stephanoetus coronatus*) and pythons (*Python*species; *Python natalensis* and *Python sebae*), while duikers of all ages may fall victim to leopards (*Panthera pardus*).
[src:african-buffalo/abbott-s-duiker] Abbott's duiker is endemic to Tanzania, in the Eastern Arc Mountains, Mount Kilimanjaro, and Southern Highlands in scattered populations.
[src:african-buffalo/abbott-s-duiker] They live mainly in wet forests and swamps between 1,700 and 2,700 m above sea level, but can sometimes wander to much higher elevations at 4,000 m.
[src:african-buffalo/abbott-s-duiker] They eat mainly fruit and possibly other plant matter.
[src:african-buffalo/abbott-s-duiker] Abbott's duikers are nocturnal, spending the days at rest in thickets.
[src:african-buffalo/abbott-s-duiker] They form regular pathways through the undergrowth, making them relatively easy to find.
[src:african-buffalo/abbott-s-duiker] If threatened, they generally try to run, though they have been known to kill pursuing dogs when left with no escape route.
[src:african-buffalo/abbott-s-duiker] Less than 1,500 Abbott's duiker are estimated to be left in the world, with no captive population.
[src:african-buffalo/abbott-s-duiker] They are threatened by habitat destruction and poaching.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] The **addax** (***Addax nasomaculatus***), also known as the **white antelope** and the **screwhorn antelope**, is an antelope native to the Sahara.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] The only member of the genus ***Addax***, it was first described scientifically by Henri de Blainville in 1816.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] As suggested by its alternative name, the addax has spiral horns that are 55 to 80 cm (22 to 31 in) long in females and 70 to 85 cm (28 to 33 in) in males.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] In the winter, its coat is greyish-brown with white hindquarters and legs, and long, brown hair on the head, neck, and shoulders; in the summer, the coat turns almost completely white or sandy blonde.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] Males stand from 105 to 115 cm (41 to 45 in) at the shoulder, with females at 95 to 110 cm (37 to 43 in).
[src:african-buffalo/addax] They are sexually dimorphic, as the females are generally smaller than the males.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] The addax lives in arid regions, semideserts, and sandy and stony deserts in North Africa.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] It mainly eats grasses and leaves of shrubs, leguminous herbs, and bushes.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] It can live without water for long periods of time.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] Addax form herds of five to 20 members, consisting of both males and females.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] The herd is usually led by one dominant male.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] Breeding season is at its peak during winter and early spring.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] The addax is listed as critically endangered on the IUCN Red List.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] It was once abundant, but is currently restricted to Chad, Mauritania, and Niger.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] It is threatened by unregulated hunting and is locally extinct in Western Sahara, Algeria, Libya, Egypt, and Sudan.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] The scientific name of the addax *Addax nasomaculatus* was proposed by Henri Marie Ducrotay de Blainville in 1816; he described a specimen in William Bullock's Pantherion and the Museum of the Royal College of Surgeons.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] Its type locality is probably in the Tunisian part of the Sahara.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] The generic name *Addax* is thought to be obtained from an Arabic word meaning a wild animal with crooked horns.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] It is also thought to have originated from a Latin word.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] The specific name *nasomaculatus* comes from the Latin words *nasus* (or the prefix *naso-*) meaning nose, and *maculatus* meaning spotted, referring to the spots and facial markings of the species.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] Bedouins use another name for the addax, the Arabic *bakr* (or *bagr*) *al wahsh*, which literally means "the cow of the wild".
[src:african-buffalo/addax] That name can be used to refer to other ungulates, as well.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] The other common names of addax are "white antelope" and "screwhorn antelope".
[src:african-buffalo/addax] All chromosomes are acrocentric except for the first pair of autosomes, which are submetacentric.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] The X chromosome is the largest of the acrocentric chromosomes, and the Y chromosome is medium-sized.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] The short and long arms of the pair of submetacentric autosomes correspond respectively to the 27th and 1st chromosomes in cattle and goats.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] In a study, the banding patterns of chromosomes in addax were found to be similar to those in four other species of the subfamily Hippotraginae.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] In ancient times, the addax occurred from northern Africa through Arabia and the Levant.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] Pictures in a tomb, dating back to 2500 BCE, show at least the partial domestication of the addax by the ancient Egyptians.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] These pictures show addax and some other antelopes tied with ropes to stakes.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] The number of addax captured by a person were considered an indicator of his high social and economic position in the society.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] The *pygarg* ("white-buttocked") beast mentioned in Deuteronomy 14:5 is believed by Henry Baker Tristram to have been an addax, but poaching has resulted in the extinction of this species in Egypt since the 1960s.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] Addax fossils have been found in four sites of Egypt – a 7000 BCE fossil from the Great Sand Sea, a 5000–6000 BCE fossil from Djara, a 4000–7000 BCE fossil from Abu Ballas Stufenmland, and a 5000 BCE fossil from Gilf Kebir.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] Apart from these, fossils have also been excavated from Mittleres Wadi Howar (6300 BCE fossil), and Pleistocene fossils from Grotte Neandertaliens, Jebel Irhoud, and Parc d'Hydra.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] The addax is greyish-brown in winter and almost completely white or sandy blonde in summer; it has white hindquarters and legs, and long, brown hair on the head, neck, and shoulders.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] Its head-to-body length is 120 to 130 cm (47 to 51 in), and its tail is 25 to 35 cm (9.8 to 13.8 in) long.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] It is sexually dimorphic in size, as males stand from 105 to 115 cm (41 to 45 in) at the shoulder with a weight of 100 to 125 kg (220 to 276 lb), whereas females are 95 to 110 cm (37 to 43 in) tall with a weight of 60 to 90 kg (130 to 200 lb).
[src:african-buffalo/addax] Their heads are marked with brown or black patches that form an X over their noses.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] They have scraggly beards and prominent red nostrils.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] Long, black hairs stick out between their curved and spiraling horns, ending in a short mane on the neck.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] The horns have two to three twists and are typically 55 to 80 cm (22 to 31 in) in females and 70 to 85 cm (28 to 33 in) in males, although the maximum recorded length is 109.2 cm (43.0 in).
[src:african-buffalo/addax] The lower and middle portions of the horns are marked with a series of 30 to 35 ring-shaped ridges.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] The tail is short and slender, ending in a puff of black hair.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] The hooves are broad with flat soles and strong dewclaws to help them walk on soft sand.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] The lifespan of the addax is up to 19 years in the wild, which can be extended to 25 years in captivity.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] The addax closely resembles the scimitar oryx, but can be distinguished by its horns and facial markings.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] While the addax is spiral-horned, the scimitar oryx has decurved, 127 cm (50 in) long horns.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] The addax has a brown hair tuft extending from the base of its horns to between its eyes.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] A white patch, continuing from the brown hair, extends until the middle of the cheek.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] The scimitar oryx, though, has a white forehead with only a notable brown marking, a brown lateral stripe across its eyes.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] It differs from other antelopes by having large, square teeth like cattle and lacking the typical facial glands.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] The addax inhabits arid regions, semideserts, and sandy and stony deserts.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] It can live in extremely arid areas, with less than 100 mm (3.9 in) annual rainfall.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] It also inhabits deserts with tussock grasses (*Stipagrostis* species) and succulent thorn scrub *Cornulaca*.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] Formerly, the addax was widespread in the Sahelo-Saharan region of Africa, west of the Nile Valley, and all countries sharing the Sahara, but today the only known self-sustaining population is present in the Termit Massif Reserve in Niger.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] Reports of sightings have been made from the eastern Air Mountains in Niger and Bodélé in Chad.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] Rare nomads may be seen in northern Niger, southern Algeria, and Libya; it is rumoured to be present along the Mali/Mauritania border, though no sightings have been confirmed.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] The addax was once abundant in North Africa, native to Chad, Mauritania, and Niger.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] It is extinct in Algeria, Egypt, Libya, Sudan, and the Western Sahara.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] It has been reintroduced into Morocco and Tunisia.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] Addax herds contain both males and females, and have from five to 20 members.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] They generally stay in one place and only wander widely in search of food.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] The herd is usually formed around one dominant male.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] In captivity, males show signs of territoriality and mate guarding, while captive females establish dominance hierarchies, with the oldest females holding highest rank.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] Herds are more likely to be found along the northern edge of the tropical rain system during the summer and move north as winter falls.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] They are able to track rainfall and head for these areas where vegetation is more plentiful.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] Males are territorial and guard females, while the females establish their own dominance hierarchies.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] Due to its slow movements, the addax is an easy target for predators, such as humans, lions, leopards, cheetahs, and African wild dogs.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] Caracals, servals, and hyenas attack calves.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] The addax is normally not aggressive, though individuals may charge if they are disturbed.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] The addax is amply suited to live in the deep desert under extreme conditions.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] It can survive without free water almost indefinitely, because it gets moisture from its food and dew that condenses on plants.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] Scientists think the addax has a special lining in its stomach that stores water in pouches to use in times of dehydration.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] It also produces highly concentrated urine to conserve water.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] The pale colour of the coat reflects radiant heat, and the length and density of the coat helps in thermoregulation.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] In the day, the addax huddles together in shaded areas, and on cool nights, rests in sand hollows.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] These practices help in dissipation of body heat and saving water by cooling the body through evaporation.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] In a study, eight addax on a diet of grass hay (*Chloris gayana*) were studied to determine the retention time of food from the digestive tract.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] Food retention time was long, possibly as an adaptation to a diet including a high proportion of slow-fermenting grasses; the long retention time also could be interpreted to be due to water-saving mechanisms with low water turnover and a roomy rumen.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] The addax lives in desert terrain where it eats grasses and leaves of what shrubs, leguminous herbs, and bushes are available.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] Primarily a grazer, its staple foods include *Aristida*, *Panicum*, and *Stipagrostis*, and it only consumes browse, such as leaves of *Acacia* trees, in the absence of these grasses.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] It also eats perennials, which turn green and sprout at the slightest bit of humidity or rain.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] The addax eats only certain parts of the plant and tends to crop the *Aristida* grasses neatly to the same height.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] By contrast, when feeding on *Panicum* grasses, the drier outer leaves are left alone while it eats the tender inner shoots and seeds.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] These seeds are important part of the addax's diet, being its main source of protein.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] Females are sexually mature at 2-3 years of age and males around 2 years.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] Breeding occurs throughout the year, but it peaks during winter and early spring.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] In the northern Sahara, breeding peaks at the end of winter and the beginning of spring; in the southern Sahara, breeding peaks from September to October and from January to mid-April.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] In a study, the blood serum of female addax was analyzed through immunoassay to know about their luteal phase.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] Estrous cycle duration was of about 33 days.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] During pregnancy, ultrasonography showed the uterine horns as coiled.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] The maximum diameters of the ovarian follicle and the corpus luteum were 15 mm (0.59 in) and 27 mm (1.1 in), respectively.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] Each female underwent an anovulatory period lasting 39 to 131 days, during which no ovulation occurred.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] Anovulation was rare in winter, which suggested the effect of seasons on the estrous cycle.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] Gestation period lasts 257–270 days (about nine months).
[src:african-buffalo/addax] Females may lie or stand during the delivery, during which one calf is born.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] A postpartum estrus occurs after 2-3 days.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] The calf weighs 5 kg (11 lb) at birth and is weaned at 23–29 weeks old.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] The addax is most prone to parasites in moist climatic conditions.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] Addax have always been infected with nematodes in the Trichostrongyloidea and Strongyloidea superfamilies.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] In an exotic ranch in Texas, an addax was found host to the nematodes *Haemonchus contortus* and *Longistrongylus curvispiculum* in its abomasum, of which the former was dominant.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] Declines in the population of the addax have been ongoing since the mid-1800s.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] More recently, addax were found from Algeria to Sudan, but due mainly to overhunting, they have become much more restricted and rare.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] Addax are easy to hunt due to their slow movements.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] Roadkill, firearms for easy hunting, and nomadic settlements near waterholes (their dry-season feeding places) have also decreased their numbers.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] Moreover, their meat and leather are highly prized.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] Other threats include chronic droughts in the deserts, habitat destruction due to more human settlements, and agriculture.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] Fewer than 500 individuals are thought to exist in the wild today, most of the animals being found between the Termit area of Niger, the Bodélé region of western Chad, and the Aoukar in Mauritania.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] Today, over 600 addax are in Europe, Yotvata Hai-Bar Nature Reserve, Sabratha, Giza Zoo, North America, Japan, and Australia under captive-breeding programmes.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] Thousands more are in private collections and ranches in the United States and the Middle East.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] Addax are legally protected in Morocco, Tunisia, and Algeria; hunting of all gazelles is forbidden in Libya and Egypt.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] The addax has been reintroduced into Bou-Hedma National Park (Tunisia) and Souss-Massa National Park (Morocco).
[src:african-buffalo/addax] Reintroductions in the wild are ongoing in Jebil National Park (Tunisia) and Grand Erg Oriental (the Sahara), and another is planned for Morocco.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] Whether any of the last remaining wild addax in western Chad near the Niger border still survive is uncertain.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] In 2019, Sahara Conservation Fund in partnership with the Environment Agency Abu Dhabi began a project to reintroduce addax to the Ouadi Rimé-Ouadi Achim Faunal Reserve, and a small population now exists there.
[src:african-buffalo/addax] In 2023, 10 addax were moved to Ennedi Natural and Cultural Reserve.
[src:african-buffalo/aders-s-duiker] The Aders's duiker stands at around 30 cm (12 in) tall at the shoulder.
[src:african-buffalo/aders-s-duiker] Its weight varies greatly depending on geographical location; those in eastern Zanzibar weigh 12 kg (26 lb), while those in the south weigh only 7.5 kg (17 lb).
[src:african-buffalo/aders-s-duiker] Its coat is reddish-brown, grayer on the neck, and lighter down the backside and underneath.
[src:african-buffalo/aders-s-duiker] It also has small, simple horns of 3 to 6 cm (1.2 to 2.4 in).
[src:african-buffalo/aders-s-duiker] The muzzle is pointed, and the nose has a flat front.
[src:african-buffalo/aders-s-duiker] The ears measure 7.0–8.3 cm (2.8–3.3 in) long, with a marked cowlick or whorl of hair on the nape of the neck.
[src:african-buffalo/aders-s-duiker] Aders's duikers live primarily in coastal forests and woodlands in Africa.
[src:african-buffalo/aders-s-duiker] The species can live in quite dry scrub near the sea or among coral outcrops; in Zanzibar, they are restricted to tall thicket forest growing on waterless coral rag.
[src:african-buffalo/aders-s-duiker] In Arabuko Sokoke (Kenya), they are most often trapped within *Cynometra* vegetation, especially on "red soil".
[src:african-buffalo/aders-s-duiker] *C. adersi* is sympatric with *C. harveyi* on the mainland and with *C. monticola sundevalli* on Zanzibar, although nothing is known regarding their ecological separation.
[src:african-buffalo/aders-s-duiker] The species is very shy, alert, and sensitive to sound.
[src:african-buffalo/aders-s-duiker] As a result, common methods of hunting include the brute-force method of driving the duikers into nets with dogs, or silent ambush at feeding sites.
[src:african-buffalo/aders-s-duiker] Aders's duikers live in coastal forests, thickets and woodlands, where they eat flowers, leaves, and fruit which has fallen from the forest canopy.
[src:african-buffalo/aders-s-duiker] The species appears to be diurnal, as it is rarely seen active at night.
[src:african-buffalo/aders-s-duiker] Typical feeding patterns are from dawn to late morning, which is followed by a period of rest and rumination.
[src:african-buffalo/aders-s-duiker] At midafternoon, Aders's duikers generally become active, and will continue foraging until nightfall.
[src:african-buffalo/aders-s-duiker] They are generally solitary or found in small groups of two or three.
[src:african-buffalo/aders-s-duiker] They often pick up scraps dropped by monkeys and birds foraging in the trees.
[src:african-buffalo/aders-s-duiker] In addition to these, they will eat sprouts, buds, and other fresh growth found at ground level.
[src:african-buffalo/aders-s-duiker] This duiker species can apparently manage without drinking, getting most of the hydration they need from their diets.
[src:african-buffalo/aders-s-duiker] These duikers have extremely specific habitat requirements, being found only in areas of old-growth thicket, with the highest population densities (11.4±5.18 per km2) recorded in relatively undisturbed high thicket.
[src:african-buffalo/aders-s-duiker] However, Kanga (1999) did report some Aders's duikers in secondary thicket.
[src:african-buffalo/aders-s-duiker] In the Arabuko-Sokoke Forest in Kenya, Aders's duikers inhabit regions of *Cyanometra* forest.
[src:african-buffalo/aders-s-duiker] Not much is known of its reproductive habits, although they may breed all year long.
[src:african-buffalo/aders-s-duiker] They are threatened by habitat destruction, feral dogs, and overhunting.
[src:african-buffalo/aders-s-duiker] They are particularly sought by humans due to their soft skin and meat.
[src:african-buffalo/aders-s-duiker] The population in Zanzibar had declined from 5000 in 1983 to 640 in 1999, and it will probably continue to decrease rapidly.
[src:african-buffalo/aders-s-duiker] In Kenya, the duiker is present at very low densities, though the decline is probably not as severe as the other population.
[src:african-buffalo/aders-s-duiker] Several conservation plans have been made, and a captive-breeding program has been proposed.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Africa straddles the equator and the prime meridian.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] The continent is surrounded by the Mediterranean Sea to the north, the Arabian plate and the Gulf of Aqaba to the northeast, the Indian Ocean to the southeast and the Atlantic Ocean to the west.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] France, Italy, Portugal, Spain, and Yemen have parts of their territories located on African geographical soil, mostly in the form of islands.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] The continent includes Madagascar and various archipelagos.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] It contains 54 fully recognised sovereign states, eight cities and islands that are part of non-African states, and two *de facto* independent states with limited or no recognition.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] This count does not include Malta and Sicily, which are geologically part of the African continent.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Algeria is Africa's largest country by area, and Nigeria is its largest by population.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] African nations cooperate through the establishment of the African Union, which is headquartered in Addis Ababa.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Africa is highly biodiverse; it is the continent with the largest number of megafauna species, as it was least affected by the extinction of the Pleistocene megafauna.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] However, Africa is also heavily affected by a wide range of environmental issues, including desertification, deforestation, water scarcity, and pollution.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] These entrenched environmental concerns are expected to worsen as climate change impacts Africa.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] The UN Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change has identified Africa as the continent most vulnerable to climate change.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] The history of Africa is long, complex, and varied, and has often been under-appreciated by the global historical community.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] In African societies the oral word is revered, and they have generally recorded their history via oral tradition, which has led anthropologists to term them "oral civilisations", contrasted with "literate civilisations" which pride the written word.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] African culture is rich and diverse both within and between the continent's regions, encompassing art, cuisine, music and dance, religion, and dress.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Africa, particularly Eastern Africa, is widely accepted to be the place of origin of humans and the Hominidae clade, also known as the great apes.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] The earliest hominids and their ancestors have been dated to around 7 million years ago, and *Homo sapiens* (modern human) are believed to have originated in Africa 350,000 to 260,000 years ago.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Throughout history the continent saw the rise and fall of many kingdoms and empires, such as Ancient Egypt, Makuria, the Fatimids, Mali, the Asante, Kongo, the Luba, Bunyoro, Great Zimbabwe, Imerina, and the Zulu.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Despite the predominance of states, many societies were heterarchical and stateless.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Slave trades created various diasporas, especially in the Americas.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] From the late-19th century to early 20th century, driven by the Second Industrial Revolution, most of Africa was rapidly conquered and colonised by European nations, save for Ethiopia and Liberia.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] European rule had significant impacts on Africa's societies, and colonies were maintained for the purpose of economic exploitation and extraction of natural resources.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Most present states emerged from a process of decolonisation following World War II, and established the Organisation of African Unity in 1963, the predecessor to the African Union.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] The nascent countries decided to keep their colonial borders, with traditional power structures used in governance to varying degrees.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Under Roman rule, Carthage became the capital of the province then named *Africa Proconsularis*, following the Roman victory over the Carthaginians in the Third Punic War in 146 BC, which also included the coastal part of modern Libya.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] The Latin suffix *-ica* can sometimes be used to denote a land (e.g., in *Celtica* from *Celtae*, as used by Julius Caesar).
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] The later Muslim region of Ifriqiya, following its conquest of the Byzantine (Eastern Roman) Empire's *Exarchatus Africae*, also preserved a form of the name.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] According to the Romans, Africa lies to the west of Egypt, while "Asia" was used to refer to Anatolia and lands to the east.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] A definite line was drawn between the two continents by the geographer Ptolemy (85–165 CE), indicating Alexandria along the Prime Meridian and making the isthmus of Suez and the Red Sea the boundary between Asia and Africa.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] As Europeans came to understand the real extent of the continent, the idea of "Africa" expanded with their knowledge.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] In accordance with African cosmology, African historical consciousness viewed historical change and continuity, order and purpose within the framework of man and his environment, the gods, and his ancestors, and he believed himself part of a holistic spiritual entity.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] In African societies, the historical process is largely a communal one, with eyewitness accounts, hearsay, reminiscences, and occasionally visions, dreams, and hallucinations crafted into narrative oral traditions which are performed and transmitted through generations.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] In oral traditions time is sometimes mythical and social, and ancestors were considered historical actors.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Mind and memory shapes traditions, as events are condensed over time and crystallise into clichés.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Oral tradition can be exoteric or esoteric.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] It speaks to people according to their understanding, unveiling itself in accordance with their aptitudes.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Africa is considered by most paleoanthropologists to be the oldest inhabited territory on Earth, with the Human species originating from the continent.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] During the mid-20th century, anthropologists discovered many fossils and evidence of human occupation perhaps as early as seven million years ago ("Before Present"; BP).
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Fossil remains of several species of early apelike humans thought to have evolved into modern humans, such as *Australopithecus afarensis* radiometrically dated to approximately 3.9–3.0 million years BP, *Paranthropus boisei* (c.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] 2.3–1.4 million years BP) and *Homo ergaster* (c.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] 1.9 million–600,000 years BP) have been discovered.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] After the evolution of *Homo sapiens* approximately 350,000 to 260,000 years BP in Africa, the continent was mainly populated by groups of hunter-gatherers.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] These first modern humans left Africa and populated the rest of the globe during the Out of Africa II migration dated to approximately 50,000 years BP, exiting the continent either across Bab-el-Mandeb over the Red Sea, the Strait of Gibraltar in Morocco, or the Isthmus of Suez in Egypt.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Other migrations of modern humans within the African continent have been dated to that time, with evidence of early human settlement found in Southern Africa, Southeast Africa, North Africa, and the Sahara.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] However, the warming and drying climate meant that by 5,000 BC, the Sahara region was becoming increasingly dry and hostile.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Around 3500 BC, due to a tilt in the Earth's orbit, the Sahara experienced a period of rapid desertification.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] The domestication of cattle in Africa preceded agriculture and seems to have existed alongside hunter-gatherer cultures.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] It is speculated that by 6,000 BC, cattle were domesticated in North Africa.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] In West Africa, a wet phase ushered in an expanding rainforest and wooded savanna from Senegal to Cameroon.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Between 9,000 and 5,000 BC, Niger–Congo speakers domesticated the oil palm and raffia palm.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Black-eyed peas and voandzeia (African groundnuts), were domesticated, followed by okra and kola nuts.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Since most of the plants grew in the forest, the Niger–Congo speakers invented polished stone axes for clearing forest.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Pygmies are thought to have inhabited Central Africa for many millennia, splitting into eastern and western groups around 5,000 BP.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Over 150,000 BP, there was an early dispersal of anatomically modern humans to Southern Africa, equated with the modern-day Khoisan who have preserved their traditional hunter-gatherer way of life.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] From 3500 BC, nomes (ruled by nomarchs) coalesced to form the kingdoms of Lower Egypt and Upper Egypt in northeast Africa.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Around 3100 BC Upper Egypt conquered Lower Egypt to unify Egypt under the 1st dynasty, with the process of consolidation and assimilation completed by the time of the 3rd dynasty who formed the Old Kingdom of Egypt in 2686 BC.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] The Kingdom of Kerma emerged around this time to become the dominant force in Nubia, controlling territory as large as Egypt between the 1st and 4th cataracts of the Nile.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] The height of the Old Kingdom saw the construction of many great pyramids, though under the 6th dynasty power gradually decentralised to the nomarchs, culminating in the disintegration of the kingdom, exacerbated by drought and famine.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Around 2055 BC, the 11th dynasty, based in Thebes, conquered the others to form the Middle Kingdom of Egypt, and the 12th dynasty expanded into Lower Nubia at the expense of Kerma.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Around 1700 BC, the Middle Kingdom fractured in two, and the Hyksos (a militaristic people from Palestine) invaded and conquered Lower Egypt, while Kerma coordinated invasions deep into Egypt to reach its greatest extent.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] In 1550 BC, the 18th dynasty expelled the Hyksos, and established the New Kingdom of Egypt.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] The New Kingdom conquered the Levant from the Canaanites, Mittani, Amorites, and Hittites, and extinguished Kerma, incorporating Nubia into the empire, and sending the Egyptian empire into its golden age.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Internal struggles, drought, famine, and invasions by a confederation of seafaring peoples contributed to the New Kingdom's collapse in 1069 BC.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] The New Kingdom's collapse liberated the Kingdom of Kush in Nubia, which manoeuvred into power in Upper Egypt and conquered Lower Egypt in 754 BC to form the Kushite Empire.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] The Kushites ruled for a century and oversaw a revival in pyramid building, until they were driven out of Egypt by the Assyrians in 663 BC in reprisal for their expansion towards the Assyrian Empire.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] The Assyrians installed a puppet dynasty that later gained independence and once more unified Egypt, until it was conquered by the Achaemenid Empire in 525 BC.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Egypt briefly regained independence from the Achaemenids under the 28th dynasty from 404 to 343 BC.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] The conquest of Achaemenid Egypt by Alexander the Great in 332 BC marked the beginning of Hellenistic rule and the installation of the Macedonian Ptolemaic dynasty in Egypt.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] The Ptolemaics lost their holdings outside of Africa to the Seleucids in the Syrian Wars, expanded into Cyrenaica, and briefly occupied part of Kush in the 3rd century BC.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] In the 1st century BC, Ptolemaic Egypt became entangled in a Roman civil war, leading to its conquest by the Romans in 30 BC.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Kush persisted as a major regional power until, having been weakened from internal rebellion amid worsening climatic conditions, invasions by Aksum and the Noba caused their disintegration into Makuria, Alodia, and Nobatia around the 5th century AD.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] In the Horn of Africa, there was the Land of Punt, a kingdom on the Red Sea which was a close trading partner of Ancient Egypt in the 3rd and 2nd millennia BC.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Rodolfo Fattovich equated it to the Gash Group in the Sudanese-Eritrean lowlands, and some scholars have hypothesised modern-day Somalia, while Kenneth Kitchen and Felix Chami locate it on Zanzibar Island.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] In the Eritrean-Ethiopian Highlands, the kingdom of dʿmt rose c.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] 980 BC as the region was incorporated into global trading networks, and it exhibited Sabaean influences which most scholars attribute to a small migration of Sabaeans and their assimilation.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Several scholars consider there to have been other contemporaneous states, and dʿmt's collapse in the mid-1st century BC saw the region inhabited by small polities.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Modern-day Somalia was inhabited by nomadic pastoralists, and along the Horn's coast there were many ancient Somali city-states that thrived off of the wider Red Sea trade, and enjoyed a lucrative monopoly on cinnamon from Ancient India due to their freedom from Roman interference.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] In the 1st century AD, the Kingdom of Aksum rose from a city-state to rule much of the northern Ethiopian-Eritrean Highlands and the Red Sea port of Adulis.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Aksum was described as one of the four great powers by Persian prophet Mani in the 3rd century.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Aksum's king converted from traditional religion to Christianity in the 4th century, gradually followed by the population.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] In the 6th century, Aksum conquered South Arabia, though struggled to maintain control over it, and began to gradually lose its dominance over Red Sea trade to Persians and Arabs.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Northwest Africa (the Maghreb) was inhabited by Berber semi-nomadic pastoralists.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] In the 1st millennium BC, Phoenician migration and settlement came in search for precious metals in the Gulf of Tunis.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] This grew into Ancient Carthage after gaining independence from Phoenicia in the 6th century BC, and they built an extensive trading empire with a strict mercantile network.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Carthage's collapse and conquest by Rome in the Punic Wars (3rd and 2nd centuries BC) saw Numidia and Mauretania become major powers in the Maghreb.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Towards the end of the 2nd century BC Mauretania fought alongside Numidia's Jugurtha against the Romans in the Jugurthine War after he had usurped the Numidian throne from a Roman ally.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Together they inflicted heavy casualties, with the war only ending inconclusively when Mauretania's Bocchus I sold out Jugurtha to the Romans.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Around the turn of the millennium, both came under direct Roman rule.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] While traditional religion predominated among Berbers, some people converted to Christianity.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] In the 5th century AD the Vandals conquered Roman Africa before the fall of Rome, though the province was reconquered by the Byzantines a century later.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Large swathes of indigenous peoples regained self-governance in Masuna and its numerous successor polities in the Maghreb, including the kingdoms of Ouarsenis, Aurès, and Altava.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] In the western Sahel the rise of settled communities occurred largely as a result of the domestication of millet and of sorghum, and cattle pastoralism began c.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Extensive east-west belts of deserts, grasslands, and forests from north to south were crucial for the moulding of their respective societies and meant that symbiotic trade relations developed in response to the differing environments.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Beginning around 4000 BC, the Tichitt culture in modern-day Mauritania and Mali is the oldest known complexly organised society in West Africa, while others included the Kintampo culture in modern-day Ghana, the Nok culture in modern-day Nigeria, and the Daima culture around Lake Chad.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Towards the end of the 3rd century AD, a wet period in the Sahel created areas for human habitation and exploitation that had not been habitable for the best part of a millennium.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] The Ghana Empire (also called *Wagadu*) rose out of the Tichitt culture, growing wealthy following the introduction of the camel to the western Sahel, which revolutionised the trans-Saharan trade that linked their capital and Aoudaghost with Tahert and Sijilmasa in North Africa.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Soninke tradition holds that the final founding of Wagadu occurred after Dinga did a deal with Bida, a serpent deity who was guarding a well, to sacrifice one maiden a year in exchange for assurance regarding plenty of rainfall and gold supply.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Based on large tumuli scattered across West Africa dating to this period, several scholars have speculated that there were further simultaneous and preceding states relative to Wagadu.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] In the Grasslands of northwestern Cameroon, Bantu-speaking agriculturalists started to gradually migrate south sometime between 5000 BC and 3000 BC.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Despite intensive research, the cause of the migrations, and that of the directions taken, is still unclear, however there is consensus that there were multiple dispersal events.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Around 1500 BC, Bantu speakers reached central Cameroon.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] The 'Western Stream' likely followed the coast and the major rivers of the Congo system southwards to reach the southern fringe of the Congolian Rainforest around 500 BC (some may have used the sea to circumvent the rainforest).
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Their arrival coincided with the spread of iron metallurgy through Central Africa.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Meanwhile, the 'Eastern Stream' travelled either the northern fringe of the rainforest or the Ubangi River eastwards, and reached just west of Lake Victoria around 500 BC.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] While there, Bantu speakers adopted iron metallurgy from Cushitic speakers already present, and coexisted with them.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Dispersal from the Great Lakes region occurred in two more streams.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] One went west to meet the Western Stream in the DR Congo and Angola, while the other went south and spread across Eastern and Southern Africa.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Around the turn of the millennium, Bantu speakers reached central modern-day Tanzania and near Dar es Salaam, before rapidly moving southwards along the coast to reach modern-day Kwazulu Natal in South Africa around the 3rd century AD.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Throughout this, Bantu speakers displaced, replaced, or intermarried with and absorbed hunter-gatherer and agricultural groups.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] In the 7th and 8th centuries, as part of the Arab conquests which sought to spread Islamic rule, the Rashidun and Umayyad caliphates conquered North Africa at the expense of the Byzantine Empire and Berber leaders such as Kusaila and Kahina.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Large numbers of Berber and Coptic people willingly converted to Islam, and followers of Abrahamic religions ('People of the Book') were protected, though followers of Berber traditional religion were violently oppressed.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] In the 8th century the Berber Revolt rocked the Caliphate and Berber dynasties took control over the Maghreb, while the Tulunids briefly controlled Egypt.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] In the 10th century, the Fatimids rose to power in modern-day Tunisia, established a rival caliphate, and conquered Egypt, before expanding into the Middle East.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] In the 11th century the Almoravids conquered the Maghreb and intervened in the Christian reconquest of Iberia.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Saladin, a Fatimid vizier, usurped power in the 12th century and established the Ayyubid dynasty which restored Egyptian prestige, while the Almohad revolution deposed the Almoravids to the east.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] After Christian gains in Iberia in the 13th century, the Almohads disintegrated into the Marinids, Zayyanids, and Hafsids in modern-day Morocco, Algeria, and Tunisia respectively.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] In the face of Mongol expansion, Mamluk generals seized power in Egypt and expanded into the Middle East.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] In the early-16th century, the Ottoman Empire rapidly conquered North Africa (save for Morocco, now under Saadi rule) to counter Spanish expansionism.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] In the following centuries, over a million Europeans are estimated to have been captured and enslaved by Barbary corsairs.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] The Ottoman regencies became more independent during the 18th century.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] In the central Sahel around Lake Chad, the Kanem–Bornu Empire ruled from the 6th century, and projected power over the Hausa Kingdoms.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] To the east during 7th century, Makuria conquered Nobatia to become the dominant power in the region and resisted Muslim expansion.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] They later entered a severe decline following civil war and Arab migrations to the Sudan and had disintegrated by the 15th century, giving rise to the Funj Sultanate.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] The Tunjur empire's collapse in the central Sudan saw the rise of the Bagirmi, Wadai, and Darfur sultanates, which frequently raided the populations to their south for slaves.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] In the Horn of Africa, Aksum lost control of the Red Sea, and its isolation from Christendom caused Ethiopian society to introspect and take inspiration from the Old Testament.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Islamised Beja invaded the Ethiopian Highlands, forcing Aksum to migrate south, where, according to tradition, Aksum's expansion was met by a Jewish or traditionalist queen who destroyed the state c.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] During the 13th century, hegemony in the Horn was contested by the Christian Zagwe, the Muslims of Shewa, and the traditionalist Damot; the Solomonic dynasty overthrew the Zagwe to found the Ethiopian Empire, while Shewa was replaced by Ifat.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Soon after, Ethiopia conquered Damot and the Muslim states, entering into a 'golden age'.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] In the 16th century Muslims united behind Adal in *jihad* to reconquer the Muslim lands and occupy Ethiopia, until, with Portuguese assistance, Ethiopia counter-attacked and its sovereignty was restored in a reduced state.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] The 16th and 17th centuries also saw Oromo invasions into the Horn, weakening Ethiopia further and causing the collapse of Adal, while Ajuran on the east coast also disintegrated.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Ethiopia briefly consolidated its authority in the late-17th century, though the turn of the century saw fragmentation and gradually-increasing anarchy, which continued throughout the 18th century.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] In the Sahel region of West Africa, the Ghana Empire formed from between the 2nd and 8th centuries, while from the 7th century the Gao Empire ruled to its east.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Almoravid capture of royal Aoudaghost led to Ghana's conversion to Islam in the 11th century, and climatic changes led to Ghana's conquest by its vassal Sosso in the 13th century.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Sosso was quickly overthrown by the Mali Empire who conquered Gao and dominated the trans-Saharan trade.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] The Mossi Kingdoms were established to its south.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] The 15th century saw the crumbling of the Mali Empire, with the dominant power in the region becoming the Songhai Empire centered on Gao.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Weakened by internal conflict, in 1591 Gao was conquered by Morocco, and the political vacuum came to be filled by the Segou Empire and several other states.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] The once lucrative trans-Saharan trade gradually lost its prominence to the coastal Atlantic trade with Europeans, and the following centuries saw many droughts, famines, and epidemics.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] In the forest regions of West Africa, various kingdoms and empires flourished, such as the Yoruba empires of Ife and Oyo, the Igbo Kingdom of Nri, the Edo Kingdom of Benin (famous for its art), the Dagomba Kingdom of Dagbon, and the Akan kingdoms of Bonoman and Adanse.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] They came into contact with the Portuguese in the 15th century which saw the start of the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] The Asante Empire was established in present-day Ghana.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Between 1515 and 1800, 8 million Africans were exported in the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] In the western Congo Basin by the 13th century there were three main confederations of states: the Seven Kingdoms, Mpemba, and one led by Vungu.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] In the 14th century the Kingdom of Kongo emerged and dominated the region, with the Tio Kingdom to its north and Mwene Muji to its northeast.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Over the course of the late-16th and 17th centuries, the Portuguese sought to conquer Ndongo (allied to Matamba) in the Angolan Wars; despite fierce resistance from Queen Nzinga, and brief occupation of Luanda by the Dutch (allied to Kongo), Portugal controlled most of Ndongo by the 1670s.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] The late-17th century saw Kongo fragment between royal houses as several vassals broke away; by the time of Kongo's restoration in 1709, it had ceased being the dominant regional power.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Also during the 17th century, in the textile-producing northeast, the Boma, Yaka, and possibly the Kuba and Pende kingdoms broke away from Mwene Muji.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] In the eastern Congo Basin, farmers, fishermen, and hunters (often Pygmies) built symbiotic relations.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Jan Vansina wrote that in the southern savanna 'lords of the land' held priestly roles due to their special relationship with the spirits of the land, and held sway over multiple villages, effectively ruling embryonic kingdoms.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Accordingly, as lineages grew, authority was opportunistically absorbed or incorporated by force.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] The centre of the Luba Empire is yet to undergo archaeological research, meaning knowledge about its rise is limited; its foundation is typically dated to the 14th/15th centuries, though scholarly estimates range from the 8th to 17th centuries.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] A Lunda state formed in the Nkalany Valley (estimates range from c.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] 1700), in the 18th century, Lunda rapidly expanded into an extensive commonwealth across the southern savanna, using the institutions of perpetual kinship and positional succession to incorporate peoples.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Meanwhile, Luba expanded its number of tributaries, in some cases using its widely acknowledged prestige to intervene in succession disputes and distribute ritually-powerful royal regalia related to *bulopwe* (sacred kingship), in other cases using conquest.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] In the northern Great Lakes, the Empire of Kitara rose around the 11th century, famed for its oral traditions.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Peter Robertshaw considered its rulers (the Chwezi) to have been religious leaders who utilised networks of hill-top shrines to project authority.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Around 1500, severe droughts and famine destabilised the region, occurring again during the early-17th and 18th centuries.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Luo-speaking peoples migrated from the Upper Nile basin into modern-day Uganda, and a Biito dynasty replaced the Chwezi in Bunyoro-Kitara.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Over the following centuries, the kingdoms of Bunyoro-Kitara, Buganda, and Rwanda struggled for hegemony among others.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Throughout the 16th and 17th centuries, Bunyoro raided states to the south such as Nkore and Rwanda.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Mpororo rose and fragmented during the 18th century, while Buganda rapidly expanded at the expense of Bunyoro to become the major power in the region.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] The East African interior was inhabited by pastoralist Cushitic and Nilotic speakers, along with Bantu speakers who continued to expand and adapt to their lands while absorbing the former two; the 17th century saw the establishment of tributary systems that stabilised the region.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] On the Swahili coast the Swahili city-states thrived off of the Indian Ocean trade and gradually Islamized, giving rise to the Kilwa Sultanate from the 10th century.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] In the 15th century, trade routes for Zimbabwean gold shifted north, weakening Kilwa.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] The Portuguese arrived at the coast soon after, and exploited divisions between coastal city-states to gain control over them while utilising a powerful navy.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] In the 17th and 18th centuries, Lamu-Swahili cities rebelled against the Portuguese and allied the Omani Empire which supplanted Portuguese rule.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Madagascar was settled by Austronesian peoples between the 5th and 7th centuries, as societies organized at the behest of *hasina* and competed over with one another over the island's estuaries and bridgeheads.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] From around the 15th century, southern Madagascar became integrated into global trade; the Sakalava Empire rose to dominate west-coastal trade, accompanied by numerous other states, and the island saw several failed European colonial ventures.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] In Southern Africa, an early kingdom was Mapungubwe, which collapsed c.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] 1300 as Great Zimbabwe, with its monumental dry-stone walls, rose to become the region's main political and economic centre.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Following shifting trade routes north to the Zambezi and unclear circumstances, Great Zimbabwe entered into decline and was succeeded by the Mutapa Empire and Kingdom of Butua in the 15th century.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Mutapa was briefly vassalised by the Portuguese in the 17th century, the latter-half of which saw widespread famine and disease, until Changamire Dombo revolted in the 1680s, conquered Butua to found the Rozvi Empire, and expelled all Portuguese from the Zimbabwean Plateau.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] North of the Zambezi, Maravi around Lake Malawi expanded in the 17th century, but the collapse of its succession system in the 18th century precipitated its disintegration.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] By the late-1st millennium CE, Bantu-speaking farmers populated most of Southern Africa's cultivable savannas, reaching southwards to the Kei River; they traded goods such as livestock, grain, and metal tools between communities and with hunter-gatherers.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Further south, the Dutch began colonizing the western Cape in the 17th century, and Britain seized control of the colony around the turn of the 19th century.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] In the late-18th century, the interplay of pre-existing trends of political centralization with the effects of international trade, environmental instability, and European colonisation set the *Mfecane* ("Crushing") in motion, as various African states were founded.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] By the turn of the 19th century, many of Africa's economic and political structures were unstable and brittle as a result of long-term effects of the slave trade.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] In Egypt Muhammad Ali led a national movement to seize power from Ottoman suzerainty, instituting sweeping reforms and greatly strengthening Egyptian power by militaristic expansion.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Meanwhile, in West Africa the Fula *jihad*s, which had been gaining momentum throughout the 18th century, culminated in the establishment of the expansive Sokoto and Hamdullahi caliphates.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] In the Horn, Ethiopia underwent reforms, seeking to revive the imperial state, something that was later achieved by Menelik II's conquests.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] In Southern Africa the *Mfecane* propelled large long-distance migrations that caused widespread disruption across the vast region, while several Boer republics were founded.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] European campaigns to abolish the Atlantic slave trade led to supply refocusing on internal markets and saw the rapid growth of the Indian Ocean slave trade.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Across the continent many rulers attempted reforms and indigenous forms of 'modernisation', however these efforts were consistently undermined by European traders and missionaries as the tide of European encroachment rose.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] For 400 years, European nations had mainly limited their involvement to trading stations on the African coast, with few daring to venture inland.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] The Industrial Revolution in Europe produced several technological innovations which assisted them in overcoming this 400-year pattern.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] One was the development of repeating rifles, which were easier and quicker to load than muskets.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Maxim developed the maxim gun, the model of the modern-day machine gun.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] European states kept these weapons largely among themselves by refusing to sell these weapons to African leaders.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] African germs took numerous European lives and deterred permanent settlements.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Diseases such as yellow fever, sleeping sickness, yaws, and leprosy made Africa a very inhospitable place for Europeans.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] The deadliest disease was malaria, endemic throughout Tropical Africa.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] In 1854, the discovery of quinine and other medical innovations helped to make conquest and colonisation in Africa possible.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] There were strong motives for the conquest of Africa.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Raw materials were needed for European factories, and free trade was championed to prevent Africans from regulating their economies.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Prestige and imperial rivalries were at play.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Acquiring African colonies would show rivals that a nation was powerful and significant.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] These contextual factors forged the Scramble for Africa; during the late-19th and early-20th centuries the European powers partitioned and conquered almost all of Africa despite fierce resistance (only Ethiopia and Liberia remained independent).
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Traditional leaders were incorporated into the colonial regimes as a form of indirect rule to extract human and natural resources and curb organized resistance.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Colonial borders were drawn unilaterally by the Europeans, often cutting across bonds of kinship, language, culture, and established routes, and sometimes incorporating groups who previously had little in common.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] The threat to trade routes was mitigated by poor policing and African entrepreneurs (viewed as smugglers) who exploited the differing tax and legal schemes.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] The first few decades of European colonialism saw intense violence, disorder, and atrocities, such as that of the Congo Free State, German South West Africa, and French Algeria, with the late colonial period relatively peaceful in comparison.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Colonial rule had wide-reaching effects on African societies, such as the spread of Christianity as part of the 'civilising mission'.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] African culture was strongly denigrated and persecuted, as pervasive racial discrimination deepened the scars of humiliation.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Imperial rule by Europeans continued until after the conclusion of World War II, when almost all remaining colonial territories gradually obtained formal independence.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Independence movements in Africa gained momentum following World War II, which left the major European powers weakened.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] In 1951, Libya, a former Italian colony, gained independence.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] In 1956, Tunisia and Morocco won their independence from France.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Ghana followed suit the next year (March 1957), becoming the first of the sub-Saharan colonies to be granted independence.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Over the next decade, waves of decolonisation took place across the continent, culminating in the 1960 Year of Africa and the establishment of the Organisation of African Unity in 1963.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Portugal's overseas presence in sub-Saharan Africa (most notably in Angola, Cape Verde, Mozambique, Guinea-Bissau, and São Tomé and Príncipe) lasted from the 16th century to 1975, after the Estado Novo regime was overthrown in a military coup in Lisbon.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Rhodesia unilaterally declared independence from the United Kingdom in 1965, under the white minority government of Ian Smith, but was not internationally recognised as an independent state (as Zimbabwe) until 1980, when black nationalists gained power after a bitter guerrilla war.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Although South Africa was one of the first African countries to gain independence, the state remained under the control of the country's white minority, initially through qualified voting rights and from 1956 by a system of racial segregation known as apartheid, until 1994.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] As of 2025, Africa contains 54 sovereign countries.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Since independence, African states have frequently been hampered by instability, corruption, violence, and authoritarianism.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] The vast majority of African states are republics that operate under some form of the presidential system of rule.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] However, few of them have been able to sustain democratic governments on a permanent basis—per the criteria laid out by Lührmann et al.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] (2018), only Botswana and Mauritius have been consistently democratic for the entirety of their post-colonial history.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Most African countries have experienced several coups or periods of military dictatorship.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Between 1990 and 2018, though, the continent as a whole has trended towards more democratic governance.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Upon independence an overwhelming majority of Africans lived in extreme poverty.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] The continent suffered from the lack of infrastructural or industrial development under colonial rule, along with political instability.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] With limited financial resources or access to global markets, relatively stable countries such as Kenya still experienced only very slow economic development.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Only a handful of African countries succeeded in obtaining rapid economic growth prior to 1990.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Exceptions include Libya and Equatorial Guinea, both of which possess large oil reserves.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Instability throughout the continent after decolonisation resulted primarily from marginalisation of ethnic groups, and corruption.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Faced with increasingly frequent and severe violence, military rule was widely accepted by the population of many countries as means to maintain order, and during the 1970s and 1980s a majority of African countries were controlled by military dictatorships.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Territorial disputes between nations and rebellions by groups seeking independence were also common in independent African states.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] The most devastating of these was the Nigerian Civil War, fought between government forces and an Igbo separatist republic, which resulted in a famine that killed 1–2 million people.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Two civil wars in Sudan, the first lasting from 1955 to 1972 and the second from 1983 to 2005, collectively killed around 3 million.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Both were fought primarily on ethnic and religious lines.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Cold War conflicts between the United States and the Soviet Union also contributed to instability.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Both the Soviet Union and the United States offered considerable incentives to African political and military leaders who aligned themselves with the superpowers' foreign policy.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] As an example, during the Angolan Civil War, the Soviet and Cuban aligned MPLA and the American aligned UNITA received the vast majority of their military and political support from these countries.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Many African countries became highly dependent on foreign aid.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] The sudden loss of both Soviet and American aid at the end of the Cold War and fall of the USSR resulted in severe economic and political turmoil in the countries most dependent on foreign support.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] There was a major famine in Ethiopia between 1983 and 1985, killing up to 1.2 million people, which most historians attribute primarily to the forced relocation of farmworkers and seizure of grain by the communist Derg government, further exacerbated by the civil war.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] In 1994 a genocide in Rwanda resulted in up to 800,000 deaths, added to a severe refugee crisis and fuelled the rise of militia groups in neighbouring countries.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] This contributed to the outbreak of the first and second Congo Wars, which were the most devastating military conflicts in modern Africa, with up to 5.5 million deaths, making it by far the deadliest conflict in modern African history and one of the costliest wars in human history.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Various conflicts between various insurgent groups and governments continue.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Since 2003, there has been an ongoing conflict in Darfur (Sudan), which peaked in intensity from 2003 to 2005 with notable spikes in violence in 2007 and 2013–15, killing around 300,000 people total.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] The Boko Haram Insurgency primarily within Nigeria (with considerable fighting in Niger, Chad, and Cameroon as well) has killed around 350,000 people since 2009.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Most African conflicts have been reduced to low-intensity conflicts as of 2022.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] However, the Tigray War from 2020 to 2022 killed an estimated 300,000–500,000 people, primarily due to famine.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Overall though, violence across Africa has greatly declined in the 21st century, with the end of civil wars in Angola, Sierra Leone, and Algeria in 2002, Liberia in 2003, and Sudan and Burundi in 2005.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] The Second Congo War, which involved 9 countries and several insurgent groups, ended in 2003.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] This decline in violence coincided with many countries abandoning communist-style command economies and opening up for market reforms, which over the course of the 1990s and 2000s promoted the establishment of permanent, peaceful trade between neighbouring countries (see Capitalist peace).
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Improved stability and economic reforms have led to a great increase in foreign investment into many African nations, mainly from China, which further spurred economic growth.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] Between 2000 and 2014, annual GDP growth in sub-Saharan Africa averaged 5.02%, doubling its total GDP from $811 billion to $1.63 trillion (constant 2015 USD).
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] North Africa experienced comparable growth rates.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] A significant part of this growth can also be attributed to the facilitated diffusion of information technologies and specifically the mobile telephone.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p01] While several individual countries have maintained high growth rates, since 2014 overall growth has considerably slowed, primarily as a result of falling commodity prices, continued lack of industrialisation, and epidemics such as Ebola and COVID-19.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Africa is the largest of the three great southward projections from the largest landmass of the Earth.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Separated from Europe by the Mediterranean Sea, it is joined to Asia at its northeast extremity by the Isthmus of Suez (transected by the Suez Canal), 163 km (101 mi) wide.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Geopolitically, Egypt's Sinai Peninsula east of the Suez Canal is often considered part of Africa as well.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] The coastline is 26,000 km (16,000 mi) long, and the absence of deep indentations of the shore is illustrated by the fact that Europe, which covers only 10,400,000 km2 (4,000,000 sq mi) – about a third of the surface of Africa – has a coastline of 32,000 km (20,000 mi).
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] From the most northerly point, Ras ben Sakka in Tunisia (37°21' N), to the most southerly point, Cape Agulhas in South Africa (34°51'15" S), is a distance of approximately 8,000 km (5,000 mi).
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Cape Verde, 17°33'22" W, the westernmost point, is a distance of approximately 7,400 km (4,600 mi) to Ras Hafun, 51°27'52" E, the most easterly projection that neighbours Cape Guardafui, the tip of the Horn of Africa.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Africa's largest country is Algeria, and its smallest country is Seychelles, an archipelago off the east coast.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] The smallest nation on the continental mainland is The Gambia.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] The African plate, also known as the Nubian plate, is a major tectonic plate that includes most of the continent of Africa (except for its easternmost part) and the adjacent oceanic crust to the west and south.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] It also includes a narrow strip of Western Asia along the Mediterranean Sea, including much of Israel, Palestine and Lebanon.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] It is bounded by the North American plate and South American plate to the west (separated by the Mid-Atlantic Ridge); the Arabian plate and Somali plate to the east; the Eurasian plate, Aegean Sea plate and Anatolian plate to the north; and the Antarctic plate to the south.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Between 60 million years ago and 10 million years ago, the Somali plate began rifting from the African plate along the East African Rift.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Since the continent of Africa consists of crust from both the African and the Somali plates, some literature refers to the African plate as the *Nubian plate* to distinguish it from the continent as a whole.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] The climate of Africa ranges from tropical to subarctic on its highest peaks.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Its northern half is primarily desert, or arid, while its central and southern areas contain both savanna plains and dense jungle (rainforest) regions.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] In between, there is a convergence, where vegetation patterns such as sahel and steppe dominate.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Africa is the hottest continent on Earth and 60% of the entire land surface consists of drylands and deserts.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] The record for the highest-ever recorded temperature, in Libya in 1922 (58 °C (136 °F)), was discredited in 2013.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Climate change in Africa is a serious threat because the continent is one of the most vulnerable regions to the effects of climate change, despite being responsible for less than 4% of global greenhouse emissions.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Climate change is causing increasingly erratic rainfall patterns, more frequent extreme weather events such as droughts, floods, and rising sea-surface temperatures across the continent.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] These changes threaten food and water security, biodiversity, public health, and economic development.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Africa is currently warming faster than the rest of the world on average.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Climate change intensifies existing socioeconomic vulnerabilities.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Large segments of the African population depend on climate-sensitive livelihoods such as agriculture (55 - 62% of the workforce in sub-Saharan Africa) and already live in poverty, heightening their exposure to shocks.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Health outcomes worsen as heat stress, vector-borne diseases (such as malaria and dengue), and malnutrition become more prevalent.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Over half (56%) of the over 2,000 recorded public health incidents in Africa between 2001 and 2021 were connected to climate change.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Resource scarcity contributes to displacement and conflict, particularly in fragile regions.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Urban areas, often characterized by informal settlements, face heightened risks from flooding and extreme heat.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Africa has over 3,000 protected areas, with 198 marine protected areas, 50 biosphere reserves, and 80 wetlands reserves.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Significant habitat destruction, increases in human population and poaching are reducing Africa's biological diversity and arable land.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Human encroachment, civil unrest and the introduction of non-native species threaten biodiversity in Africa.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] This has been exacerbated by administrative problems, inadequate personnel and funding problems.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Deforestation is affecting Africa at twice the world rate, according to the United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP).
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] The deforestation rate of 4.08 million hectares in 2000–2015 declined to 3.45 million ha per year in 2015–2025.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Some sources claim that approximately 90% of the original, virgin forests in West Africa have been destroyed.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Over 90% of Madagascar's original forests have been destroyed since the arrival of humans 2000 years ago.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] About 65% of Africa's agricultural land suffers from soil degradation.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] It is also home to a variety of "jungle" animals including snakes and primates and aquatic life such as crocodiles and amphibians.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] In addition, Africa has the largest number of megafauna species, as it was least affected by the extinction of the Pleistocene megafauna.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] African environmental problems are problems caused by the direct and indirect human impacts on the natural environment and affect humans and nearly all forms of life in Africa.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Issues include deforestation, soil degradation, air pollution, water pollution, coastal erosion, garbage pollution, climate change, Oil spills, Biodiversity loss, and water scarcity (resulting in problems with access to safe water supply and sanitation).
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] These issues result in environmental conflict and are connected to broader social struggles for democracy and sovereignty.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] The scarcity of climate adaptation techniques in Africa makes it the least resilient continent to climate change.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] The African Union (AU) is a continental union consisting of 55 member states.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] The union was formed, with Addis Ababa, Ethiopia, as its headquarters, on 26 June 2001.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] The union was officially established on 9 July 2002 as a successor to the Organisation of African Unity (OAU).
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] In July 2004, the African Union's Pan-African Parliament (PAP) was relocated to Midrand, in South Africa, but the African Commission on Human and Peoples' Rights remained in Addis Ababa.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] The African Union, not to be confused with the AU Commission, is formed by the Constitutive Act of the African Union, which aims to transform the African Economic Community, a federated commonwealth, into a state under established international conventions.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] The African Union has a parliamentary government, known as the African Union Government, consisting of legislative, judicial and executive organs.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] It is led by the African Union President and Head of State, who is also the President of the Pan-African Parliament.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] A person becomes AU President by being elected to the PAP, and subsequently gaining majority support in the PAP.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] The government of the AU consists of all-union, regional, state, and municipal authorities, as well as hundreds of institutions, that together manage the day-to-day affairs of the institution.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Extensive human rights abuses still occur in several parts of Africa, often under the oversight of the state.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Most of such violations occur for political reasons, often as a side effect of civil war.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Countries where major human rights violations have been reported in recent times include the Democratic Republic of the Congo, Sierra Leone, Liberia, Sudan, Zimbabwe, and Ivory Coast.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] African nations have made great efforts to respect international borders as inviolate for a long time.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] For example, the Organization of African Unity (OAU), which was established in 1963 and replaced by the African Union in 2002, set the respect for the territorial integrity of each country as one of its principles in OAU Charter.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Indeed, compared with the formation of European countries, there have been fewer international conflicts in Africa for changing the borders, which has influenced country formation there and has enabled some countries to survive that might have been defeated and absorbed by others.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Yet international conflicts have played out by support for proxy armies or rebel movements.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Many states have experienced civil wars: including Rwanda, Sudan, Angola, Sierra Leone, Congo, Liberia, Ethiopia and Somalia.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Wars of national liberation also often took up a Marxist, Marxist–Leninist, or Maoist character in ideological terms, where the independence of African nations was raised in Marxian terms.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Early examples included the Union of the Peoples of Cameroon armed movement against French colonialism, a Marxist–Leninist insurgency, followed by similar movements in Congo (the Simba Rebellion).
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Che Guevara participated in the latter, and opined in 1967 that Africa was not ready for revolution.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Despite this, in Zanzibar before and after unification with Tanzania, forms of socialism took hold.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Even after 1990, there are some examples of Military Marxism, such as a militia established by Ernest Wamba-dia-Wamba in Eastern Congo in the 1990s.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] The countries in this table are categorised according to the scheme for geographic subregions used by the United Nations, and data included are per sources in cross-referenced articles.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Where they differ, provisos are clearly indicated.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] This list contains nine territories that are administered as incorporated areas of a primarily non-African country but that belong geographically to the African continent.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] The continent's total nominal GDP remains behind that of several individual countries, including the United States, China, Japan, Germany, the United Kingdom, India and France.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] According to the United Nations' Human Development Report in 2003, the bottom 24 ranked nations (151st to 175th) were all African.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Poverty, illiteracy, malnutrition, inadequate water supply and sanitation, and poor health affect a large proportion of the people who reside on the African continent.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] In August 2008, the World Bank announced revised global poverty estimates based on a new international poverty line of $1.25 per day (versus the previous measure of $1.00).
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Eighty-one percent of the sub-Saharan African population was living on less than $2.50 (PPP) per day in 2005, compared with 86% for India.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Sub-Saharan Africa is the least successful region of the world in reducing poverty ($1.25 per day); some 50% of the population living in poverty in 1981 (200 million people), a figure that rose to 58% in 1996 before dropping to 50% in 2005 (380 million people).
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] The average poor person in sub-Saharan Africa is estimated to live on only 70 cents per day, and was poorer in 2003 than in 1973, indicating increasing poverty in some areas.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Some of it is attributed to unsuccessful economic liberalisation programmes spearheaded by foreign companies and governments, but other studies have cited bad domestic government policies more than external factors.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Africa is now at risk of being in debt once again, particularly in sub-Saharan African countries.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] The last debt crisis in 2005 was resolved with help from the heavily indebted poor countries scheme (HIPC).
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] The HIPC resulted in some positive and negative effects on the economy in Africa.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] About ten years after the 2005 debt crisis in sub-Saharan Africa was resolved, Zambia fell back into debt.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] A small reason was due to the fall in copper prices in 2011, but the bigger reason was that a large amount of the money Zambia borrowed was wasted or pocketed by the elite.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] From 1995 to 2005, Africa's rate of economic growth increased, averaging 5% in 2005.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Some countries experienced still higher growth rates, notably Angola, Sudan and Equatorial Guinea, all of which had recently begun extracting their petroleum reserves or had expanded their oil extraction capacity.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] The following table shows the projected nominal GDP and GDP per capita (at purchasing power parity) in 2026 by the IMF.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] The continent is believed to hold 90% of the world's cobalt, 90% of its platinum, 50% of its gold, 98% of its chromium, 70% of its tantalite, 64% of its manganese and one-third of its uranium.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] The Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) has 70% of the world's coltan, a mineral used in the production of tantalum capacitors for electronic devices such as cell phones.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] The DRC also has more than 30% of the world's diamond reserves.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Guinea is the world's largest exporter of bauxite.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] As the growth in Africa has been driven mainly by services and not manufacturing or agriculture, it has been growth without jobs and without reduction in poverty levels.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] In fact, the food security crisis of 2008, which took place following the global financial crisis, pushed 100 million people into food insecurity.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] In 2024 nearly 307 million people in Africa were undernourished (46% of the global total), an increase of 10 million people since 2023 and 34 million from 2022.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] In recent years, China has built increasingly stronger ties with African nations and is Africa's largest trading partner.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] In 2007, Chinese companies invested a total of US$1 billion in Africa.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] A Harvard University study led by professor Calestous Juma showed that Africa could feed itself by making the transition from importer to self-sufficiency.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] "African agriculture is at the crossroads; we have come to the end of a century of policies that favoured Africa's export of raw materials and importation of food.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Cooking with biogas in Tanzania; Geothermal energy infrastructure in Kenya; Coal power station in South Africa; Solar-powered lamp-light in Zambia.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Energy in Africa is characterised by low per-capita consumption and limited access to modern energy services, reflecting both infrastructural and socio-economic challenges across the continent.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] As of 2023, Africa accounted for just 5.5% of global total final energy consumption, with per-capita energy use more than three times lower than the global average.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] The energy mix is dominated by biofuels and waste, which make up 43% of total final consumption, primarily for household cooking and heating, followed by oil products at 33%, electricity at 11%, natural gas at 9%, and coal at 4%.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Electricity access remains a major challenge, particularly in Sub-Saharan Africa, where nearly 450 million rural residents lack reliable electricity, and grid coverage is often inconsistent.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Clean cooking solutions are similarly underdeveloped, leaving over 900 million people reliant on polluting fuels such as firewood, charcoal, and agricultural residues, which disproportionately affect women and children.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Transport energy is dominated by oil products, reflecting low motorisation rates and limited adoption of electric mobility, although countries such as Ethiopia, Morocco, and Egypt have begun adopting policies to reduce fossil fuel dependency.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Africa possesses some of the world's most abundant energy resources, including oil, natural gas, coal, hydropower, solar, wind, geothermal, and biomass, much of which remains underutilised.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] While fossil fuels such as coal, oil, and natural gas continue to dominate energy production and electricity generation in Africa, renewable sources are increasingly expanding across the continent.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Hydropower, solar, wind, geothermal, and modern biomass are growing in capacity, though their deployment remains uneven and limited compared to the continent's vast potential.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Hydropower is the largest non-combustible renewable source, while solar energy offers immense potential due to high irradiation levels, particularly in the Sahara and Sahel.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] There are regional differences: North Africa is dominated by oil and gas production, Southern Africa by coal and hydropower, East Africa by hydropower and geothermal, and West and Central Africa face major electrification gaps despite hydroelectric potential.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Water development and management are complex in Africa due to the multiplicity of trans-boundary water resources (rivers, lakes and aquifers).
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Around 75% of sub-Saharan Africa falls within 53 international river basin catchments that traverse multiple borders.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] This particular constraint can also be converted into an opportunity if the potential for trans-boundary cooperation is harnessed in the development of the area's water resources.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] A multi-sectoral analysis of the Zambezi River, for example, shows that riparian cooperation could lead to a 23% increase in firm energy production without any additional investments.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] A number of institutional and legal frameworks for transboundary cooperation exist, such as the Zambezi River Authority, the Southern African Development Community (SADC) Protocol, Volta River Authority and the Nile Basin Commission.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] However, additional efforts are required to further develop political will, as well as the financial capacities and institutional frameworks needed for win-win multilateral cooperative actions and optimal solutions for all riparians.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Africa is considered by anthropologists to be the most genetically diverse continent as a result of being the longest inhabited.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Africa's population has rapidly increased over the last 40 years, and is consequently relatively young.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] In some African states, more than half the population is under 25 years of age.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] The total number of people in Africa increased from 229 million in 1950 to 630 million in 1990.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] As of 2021, the population of Africa is estimated at 1,394 million.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Africa's total population surpassing other continents is fairly recent; African population surpassed Europe in the 1990s, while the Americas was overtaken sometime around the year 2000.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] This increase in number of babies born in Africa compared to the rest of the world is expected to reach approximately 37% in the year 2050; while in 1990 sub-Saharan Africa accounted for only 16% of the world's births.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] The total fertility rate (children per woman) for Sub-Saharan Africa is 4.7 as of 2018, the highest in the world.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] All countries in sub-Saharan Africa had TFRs (average number of children) above replacement level in 2019 and accounted for 27.1% of global livebirths.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] In 2021, sub-Saharan Africa accounted for 29% of global births.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Speakers of Bantu languages (part of the Niger–Congo family) are the majority in southern, central and southeast Africa.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] The Bantu-speaking peoples from the Sahel progressively expanded over most of sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] But there are also several Nilotic groups in South Sudan and East Africa, the mixed Swahili people on the Swahili Coast, and a few remaining indigenous Khoisan ("San" or "Bushmen") and Pygmy peoples in Southern and Central Africa, respectively.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Bantu-speaking Africans also predominate in Gabon and Equatorial Guinea, and are found in parts of southern Cameroon.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] In the Kalahari Desert of Southern Africa, the distinct people known as the Bushmen (also "San", closely related to, but distinct from "Hottentots") have long been present.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] The San are physically distinct from other Africans and are the indigenous people of southern Africa.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Pygmies are the pre-Bantu indigenous peoples of central Africa.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] The peoples of West Africa primarily speak Niger–Congo languages, belonging mostly to its non-Bantu branches, though some Nilo-Saharan and Afro-Asiatic speaking groups are also found.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] The Niger–Congo-speaking Yoruba, Igbo, Fulani, Akan, and Wolof ethnic groups are the largest and most influential.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] In the central Sahara, Mandinka or Mande groups are most significant.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Chadic-speaking groups, including the Hausa, are found in more northerly parts of the region nearest to the Sahara, and Nilo-Saharan communities, such as the Songhai, Kanuri, and Zarma, are found in the eastern parts of West Africa bordering Central Africa.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] The peoples of North Africa consist of three main indigenous groups: Berbers in the northwest, Egyptians in the northeast, and Nilo-Saharan-speaking peoples in the east.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] The Arabs who arrived in the 7th century AD introduced the Arabic language and Islam to North Africa.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] The Semitic Phoenicians (who founded Carthage) and Hyksos, the Indo-Iranian Alans, the Indo-European Greeks, Romans, and Vandals settled in North Africa as well.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Significant Berber communities remain within Morocco and Algeria in the 21st century, while, to a lesser extent, Berber speakers are also present in some regions of Tunisia and Libya.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] The Berber-speaking Tuareg and other often-nomadic peoples are the principal inhabitants of the Saharan interior of North Africa.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] In Mauritania, there is a small but near-extinct Berber community in the north and Niger–Congo-speaking peoples in the south, though in both regions Arabic and Arab culture predominates.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] In Sudan, although Arabic and Arab culture predominate, it is mostly inhabited by groups that originally spoke Nilo-Saharan, such as the Nubians, Fur, Masalit and Zaghawa, who, over the centuries, have variously intermixed with migrants from the Arabian peninsula.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Small communities of Afro-Asiatic-speaking Beja nomads can also be found in Egypt and Sudan.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] In the Horn of Africa, some Ethiopian and Eritrean groups (like the Amhara and Tigrayans, collectively known as Habesha) speak languages from the Semitic branch of the Afro-Asiatic language family, while the Oromo and Somali speak languages from the Cushitic branch of Afro-Asiatic.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Prior to the decolonisation movements of the post-World War II era, Europeans were represented in every part of Africa.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Decolonization during the 1960s and 1970s often resulted in the mass emigration of white settlers—especially from Algeria and Morocco (1.6 million *pieds-noirs* in North Africa), Kenya, Congo, Rhodesia, Mozambique and Angola.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Between 1975 and 1977, over a million colonials returned to Portugal alone.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Nevertheless, white Africans remain an important minority in many African states, particularly Zimbabwe, Namibia, Réunion, and South Africa.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] The country with the largest white African population is South Africa.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Dutch and British diasporas represent the largest communities of European ancestry on the continent today.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] European colonisation also brought sizable groups of Asians, particularly from the Indian subcontinent, to British colonies.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Large Indian communities are found in South Africa, and smaller ones are present in Kenya, Tanzania, and some other southern and southeast African countries.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] The large Indian community in Uganda was expelled by the dictator Idi Amin in 1972, though many have since returned.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] The islands in the Indian Ocean are also populated primarily by people of Asian origin, often mixed with Africans and Europeans.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] The Malagasy people of Madagascar are an Austronesian people, but those along the coast are generally mixed with Bantu, Arab, Indian and European origins.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Malay and Indian ancestries are also important components in the group of people known in South Africa as Cape Coloureds (people with origins in two or more races and continents).
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] During the 20th century, small but economically important communities of Lebanese have also developed in the larger coastal cities of West and East Africa, respectively.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] The Sahara served as a trans-regional passageway and place of dwelling for people in Africa during various humid phases and periods throughout the history of Africa.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] As early as 11,000 years ago, Sub-Saharan West Africans, bearing macrohaplogroup L (e.g., L1b1a11, L1b1a6a, L1b1a8, L1b1a9a1, L2a1k, L3d1b1a), may have migrated through North Africa and into Europe, mostly into southern Europe (e.g., Iberia).
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] The genetic marker E1b1 was identified to have wide distribution across Egypt, with "P2/215/M35.1 (E1b1b), for short M35, likely also originated in eastern tropical Africa, and is predominantly distributed in an arc from the Horn of Africa up through Egypt".
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] The R haplogroup has also been identified to have high frequencies in central Saharan Africa, among some Afro-Asiatic and Nilo-Saharan language speaking groups.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Genetic evidence has identified the Horn of Africa to be the source of a genetic marker "M35/215" Y-chromosome lineage for a significant population component which moved north from that region into Egypt and the Levant.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Historian Christopher Ehret argued that this genetic distribution paralleled the spread of the Afrasian language family with the movement of people from the Horn of Africa into Egypt and added a new demic component to the existing population of Egypt 17,000 years ago.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] According to a recent study, the Arab migrations to the Maghreb was mainly a demographic process that heavily implied gene flow and remodelled the genetic structure of the Maghreb region in North Africa, rather than a mere cultural replacement as claimed by older studies.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Another study found out that the majority of J-M267 (Eu10) chromosomes in the Maghreb are due to the recent gene flow caused by the Arab migrations to the Maghreb in the first millennium CE as both southern Qahtanite and northern Adnanite Arabs added to the heterogenous Maghrebi ethnic melting pot.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] The Eu10 chromosome pool in the Maghreb is derived not only from early Neolithic dispersions from Western Asia but to a much greater extent from recent expansions of Arab tribes from the Arabian Peninsula.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] David Schoenbrun, Christopher Ehret, Steven A.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Brandt and Shomarka Keita (2025) have highlighted the problematic categorisation of genetic haplogroups characterised as ‘African’ and ‘Eurasian' in North African genome studies.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] In reference to the van de Loosdrecht et al.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] In their view, identifying a range of African populations may still remain an issue “since the idea of ‘African’ still gets stereotyped or restricted.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] (Accepting the southwestern Asian/Levantine geographical continuity with Africa eliminates a conceptual barrier related to racio-typological thinking permitting an Africasian construct analogous to Eurasian.)”.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] While Africans profess a wide variety of religious beliefs, the majority of the people respect African religions or parts of them.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] However, in formal surveys or census, most people will identify with major religions that came from outside the continent, mainly through colonisation.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] There are several reasons for this, the main one being the colonial idea that African religious beliefs and practices are not good enough.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Religious beliefs and statistics on religious affiliation are difficult to come by since they are often a sensitive topic for governments with mixed religious populations.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] According to the *World Book Encyclopedia*, Islam and Christianity are the two largest religions in Africa.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Islam is most prevalent in Northern Africa, and is the state religion of many North African countries, such as Algeria, where 99% of the population practices Islam.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] The majority of people in most governments in Southern, Southeast, and Central Africa, as well as in a sizable portion of the Horn of Africa and West Africa, identify as Christians.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] The Coptic Christians constitute a sizable minority in Egypt, and the Ethiopian Orthodox Church is the largest church in Ethiopia, with 36 million and 51 million adherents.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] According to Encyclopædia Britannica, 45% of the population are Christians, 40% are Muslims, and 10% follow traditional religions.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] A small number of Africans are Hindu, Buddhist, Confucianist, Baháʼí, or Jewish.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] There is also a minority of people in Africa who are irreligious.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] By most estimates, well over a thousand languages (UNESCO has estimated around two thousand) are spoken in Africa.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Most are of African origin, though some are of European or Asian origin.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Africa is the most multilingual continent in the world, and it is not rare for individuals to fluently speak not only multiple African languages, but one or more European ones as well.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Following the end of colonialism, nearly all African countries adopted official languages that originated outside the continent, although several countries also granted legal recognition to indigenous languages (such as Swahili, Yoruba, Igbo and Hausa).
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] In numerous countries, English and French (*see African French*) are used for communication in the public sphere such as government, commerce, education and the media.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Arabic, Portuguese, Afrikaans and Spanish are examples of languages that trace their origin to outside of Africa, and that are used by millions of Africans today, both in the public and private spheres.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Italian is spoken by some in former Italian colonies in Africa.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] German is spoken in Namibia, as it was a former German protectorate.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] In total, at least a fifth of Africans speak the former colonial languages.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Moreover, in recent years some African countries have been considering removing their official former colonial languages, such as Mali, Burkina Faso and Niger which removed French as an official language in the 2020s in favour of native languages, while also renaming colonial street names.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] More than 85% of individuals in Africa use traditional medicine as an alternative to often expensive allopathic medical health care and costly pharmaceutical products.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] AIDS in post-colonial Africa is a prevalent issue.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Although the continent is home to about 15.2 percent of the world's population, more than two-thirds of the total infected worldwide—some 35 million people—were Africans, of whom 15 million have already died.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Sub-Saharan Africa alone accounted for an estimated 69 percent of all people living with HIV and 70 percent of all AIDS deaths in 2011.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] In the countries of sub-Saharan Africa most affected, AIDS has raised death rates and lowered life expectancy among adults between the ages of 20 and 49 by about twenty years.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p02] Furthermore, the life expectancy in many parts of Africa has declined, largely as a result of the HIV/AIDS epidemic with life-expectancy in some countries reaching as low as thirty-four years.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] Africa is divided into a great number of ethnic cultures.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] In recent times, the call for a much greater emphasis on the cultural dimension in all aspects of development has become increasingly vocal.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] Some aspects of traditional African cultures have become less practised in recent years as a result of neglect and suppression by colonial and post-colonial regimes.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] For example, African customs were discouraged, and African languages were prohibited in mission schools, while colonialists such as Leopold II of Belgium attempted to "civilize" Africans by discouraging polygamy and witchcraft.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] Abiola Irele and Simon Gikandi comment that the current identity of African literature had its genesis in the "traumatic encounter between Africa and Europe".
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] On the other hand, Mhoze Chikowero believes that Africans deployed music, dance, spirituality, and other performative cultures to (re)assert themselves as active agents and indigenous intellectuals, to unmake their colonial marginalisation and reshape their own destinies.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] As of March 2023, 98 African properties are listed by UNESCO as World Heritage Sites.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] Among these proprieties, 54 are cultural sites, 39 are natural sites and 5 are mixed sites.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] The List of World Heritage in Danger includes 15 African sites.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] African art refers to works of visual art, including works of sculpture, painting, metalwork, and pottery, originating from the various peoples of the African continent and influenced by distinct, indigenous traditions of aesthetic expression.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] While the various artistic traditions of such a large and diverse continent display considerable regional and cultural variety, there are consistent artistic themes, recurring motifs, and unifying elements across the broad spectrum of the African visual expression.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] As is the case for every artistic tradition in human history, African art was created within specific social, political, and religious contexts.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] Likewise, African art was often created not purely for art's sake, but rather with some practical, spiritual, and/or didactic purpose in mind.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] In general, African art prioritizes conceptual and symbolic representation over realism, aiming to visualize the subject's spiritual essence.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] Ethiopian art, heavily influenced by Ethiopia's long-standing Christian tradition, is also different from most African art, where Traditional African religion (with Islam prevalent in the north east and north west presently) was dominant until the 20th century.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] African art includes prehistoric and ancient art, the Islamic art of West Africa, the Christian art of East Africa, and the traditional artifacts of these and other regions.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] Many African sculptures were historically made of wood and other natural materials that have not survived from earlier than a few centuries ago, although rare older pottery and metal figures can be found in some areas.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] Some of the earliest decorative objects, such as shell beads and evidence of paint, have been discovered in Africa, dating to the Middle Stone Age.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] Masks are important elements in the art of many people, along with human figures, and are often highly stylized.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] There exist diverse styles, which can often be observed within a single context of origin and may be influenced by the intended use of the object.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] Nevertheless, broad regional trends are discernible.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] Sculpture is most common among "groups of settled cultivators in the areas drained by the Niger and Congo rivers" in West Africa.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] Direct images of deities are relatively infrequent, but masks in particular are or were often made for ritual ceremonies.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] Since the late 19th century, there has been an increasing amount of African art in Western collections, the finest pieces of which are displayed as part of the history of colonization.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] African art had an important influence on European Modernist art, which was inspired by their interest in abstract depiction.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] It was this appreciation of African sculpture that has been attributed to the very concept of "African art", as seen by European and American artists and art historians.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] Obidoh Freeborn posits that colonialism is one element that has created the character of modern African art.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] According to authors Douglas Fraser and Herbert M.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] Author Chika Okeke-Agulu states that "the racist infrastructure of British imperial enterprise forced upon the political and cultural guardians of empire a denial and suppression of an emergent sovereign Africa and modernist art".
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] scaling: small parts of the structure tend to look similar to larger parts, such as a circular village made of circular houses.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] African architecture in some areas has been influenced by external cultures for centuries, according to available evidence.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] Western architecture has influenced coastal areas since the late 15th century and is now an important source of inspiration for many larger buildings, particularly in major cities.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] African architecture uses a wide range of materials, including thatch, stick/wood, mud, mudbrick, rammed earth, and stone.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] These material preferences vary by region: North Africa for stone and rammed earth, the Horn of Africa for stone and mortar, West Africa for mud/adobe, Central Africa for thatch/wood and more perishable materials, Southeast and Southern Africa for stone and thatch/wood.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] Cinema of Africa refers to the film industries and films produced in the continent of Africa.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] It covers both the history and present of the making or screening of films on the African continent, and also refers to the persons involved in this form of audiovisual culture.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] It dates back to the late 19th century, when film reels were the primary cinematic technology in use.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] Cairo has been the capital of film industry in Africa since the early 20th century to the present day.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] As there are more than 50 countries with audiovisual traditions, there is no one single 'African cinema'.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] Both historically and culturally, there are major regional differences between North African and sub-Saharan cinemas, and between the cinemas of different countries.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] The Egyptian film industry and the Tunisian are also among the oldest in the world.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] Cinema of Egypt in particular is the most established and flourishing industry in Africa.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] Pioneers Auguste and Louis Lumière screened their films in Alexandria, Cairo, Tunis, Susa, Libya and Hammam-Lif, Tunisia in 1896.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] Albert Samama Chikly is often cited as the first producer of indigenous African cinema, screening his own short documentaries in the casino of Tunis as early as December 1905.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] The continent of Africa and its music is vast and highly diverse, with different regions and nations maintaining distinct musical traditions.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] African music includes genres such as makwaya, highlife, mbube, township music, jùjú, fuji, jaiva, afrobeat, afrofusion, mbalax, Congolese rumba, soukous, ndombolo, makossa, kizomba, and taarab, among others.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] African music also uses a wide variety of instruments from across the continent.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] The music and dance traditions of the African diaspora, shaped to varying degrees by African musical traditions, include American genres such as Dixieland jazz, blues, and jazz, as well as Caribbean styles such as calypso (see kaiso), and soca.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] Latin American music genres including cumbia, salsa, son cubano, rumba, conga, bomba, samba, and zouk developed from the music of enslaved Africans and have, in turn, influenced contemporary African popular music.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] African dance (also Afro dance, Afrodance and Afro-dance) refers to the various dance styles of sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] These dances are closely connected with the traditional rhythms and music traditions of the region.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] Music and dancing is an integral part of many traditional African societies.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] Songs and dances facilitate teaching and promoting social values, the celebration of special events and major life milestones, the performance of oral history and other recitations, and spiritual experiences.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] African dance uses the concepts of polyrhythm and total body articulation.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] African dances are often a collective activity performed in large groups, with significant interaction between dancers and onlookers.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] Fifty-four African countries have football teams in the Confederation of African Football.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] Egypt has won the African Cup seven times, and a record-making three times in a row.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] Cameroon, Nigeria, Morocco, Senegal, Ghana, and Algeria have advanced to the knockout stage of recent FIFA World Cups.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] Morocco, at the 2022 World Cup in Qatar was the first African nation to reach the semi-finals of the FIFA Men's World Cup.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] South Africa hosted the 2010 World Cup tournament, becoming the first African country to do so.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] The top clubs in each African football league play the CAF Champions League, while lower-ranked clubs compete in CAF Confederation Cup.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] In recent years, the continent has progressed in terms of state-of-the-art basketball facilities, which have been built in cities such as Cairo, Dakar, Johannesburg, Kigali, Luanda, and Rades.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] The number of African basketball players who drafted into the U.S.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] NBA has experienced growth in the 2010s.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] Cricket is popular in some African nations.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] South Africa and Zimbabwe have Test status, while Kenya is the leading non-test team and previously had One-Day International cricket (ODI) status (from 10 October 1997, until 30 January 2014).
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] The three countries jointly hosted the 2003 Cricket World Cup.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] Namibia is the other African country to have played in a World Cup.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] Morocco, in northern Africa, hosted the 2002 Morocco Cup, but the national team has never qualified for a major tournament.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] Rugby is popular in several southern African nations.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] Namibia and Zimbabwe have appeared on multiple occasions at the Rugby World Cup, while South Africa is the most successful national team at the Rugby World Cup, having won the tournament on four occasions, in 1995, 2007, 2019, and 2023.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] Traditional sports were strictly marginalised during the colonial era, and many are dying or have gone extinct under the pressure of modernisation, however lots remain popular despite not having formal governmental recognition or support.
[src:african-buffalo/africa-p03] Some examples are Senegalese wrestling, Dambe, Nguni stick-fighting, and Savika.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] The **African buffalo** (***Syncerus caffer***) is a large species of true buffalo native to Sub-Saharan Africa, where it is found in a number of disconnected ranges stretching from south-eastern Senegal through West and Central Africa to South Africa.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] The adult African buffalo's horns are its characteristic feature: they have fused bases that form a continuous bone shield, referred to as a "boss", across the top of the head.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] The African buffalo is more closely related to Asian buffalo (*Bubalus*) species than it is to other bovids such as American bison or domestic cattle.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] Its unpredictable temperament may be part of the reason that the African buffalo has never been domesticated and has no domesticated descendants, unlike the wild yak and wild water buffalo, which are the ancestors of the domestic yak and water buffalo, respectively.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] Natural predators of adult African buffaloes include lions, African wild dogs, spotted hyenas, and Nile crocodiles.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] As one of the Big Five game animals, the **Cape buffalo** (*Syncerus caffer caffer*), the largest subspecies native to eastern and southern Africa, is a sought-after trophy in hunting.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] The African buffalo is a very robust species.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] Its shoulder height can range from 1.0 to 1.7 m (3 ft 3 in to 5 ft 7 in) and its head-and-body length can range from 1.7 to 3.4 m (5 ft 7 in to 11 ft 2 in).
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] The tail can range from 70 to 110 cm (2 ft 4 in to 3 ft 7 in) long.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] Compared with other large bovids, it has a long but stocky body (the body length can exceed that of the wild water buffalo, which is heavier and taller) and short but thickset legs, resulting in a relatively short standing height.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] Cape buffaloes weigh 425 to 870 kg (937 to 1,918 lb) (males weigh about 100 kg (220 lb) more than females).
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] In comparison, African forest buffaloes, at 250 to 450 kg (600 to 1,000 lb), are only half that size.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] Its head is carried low; its top is located below the backline.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] The front hooves of the buffalo are wider than the rear, which is associated with the need to support the weight of the front part of the body, which is heavier and more powerful than the back.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] Savannah-type buffaloes have black or dark brown coats with age.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] Old bulls often have whitish circles around their eyes and on their face.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] Females tend to have more reddish coats.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] Forest-type buffaloes are 30–40% smaller, reddish brown in colour, with much more hair growth around the ears and with horns that curve back and slightly up.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] A characteristic feature of the horns of adult male African buffalo (southern and eastern populations) is that the bases come very close together, forming a shield referred to as a "boss".
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] From the base, the horns diverge downwards, then smoothly curve upwards and outwards and in some cases inwards and or backwards.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] In large bulls, the distance between the ends of the horns can reach upwards of one metre (the record being 164 cm (5 ft 5 in)).
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] The horns form fully when the animal reaches the age of 5 or 6 years old, but the bosses do not become "hard" until it reaches the age of 8 to 9 years old.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] In cows, the horns are, on average, 10–20% smaller, and they do not have a boss.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] Forest-type buffalo horns are smaller than those of the savanna-type buffaloes from Southern and East Africa, usually measuring less than 40 cm (16 in), and are almost never fused.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] Unlike other large bovines, African buffalo have 52 chromosomes (for comparison, American bison and domestic cattle have 60).
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] This means they are unable to produce hybrid offspring with domestic cattle and bison.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] The African buffalo is one of the most successful grazers in Africa.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] It lives in savannas, swamps and floodplains, as well as mopane grasslands, and the forests of the major mountains of Africa.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] This buffalo prefers a habitat with dense cover, such as reeds and thickets, but can also be found in open woodland.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] While not particularly demanding in regard to habitat, they require water daily, and so they depend on perennial sources of water.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] Like the plains zebra, the buffalo can live on tall, coarse grasses.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] Herds of buffalo mow down grasses and make way for more selective grazers.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] When feeding, the buffalo makes use of its tongue and wide incisor row to eat grass more quickly than most other African herbivores.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] Buffaloes do not stay on trampled or depleted areas for long.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] Other than humans, African buffaloes have few predators and are capable of defending themselves against (and killing) lions.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] Lions kill and eat buffaloes regularly, and in some regions, the buffaloes are the lions' primary prey.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] It often takes several lions to bring down a single adult buffalo, and the entire pride may join in the hunt.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] However, several incidents have been reported in which lone adult male lions have successfully brought down adult buffaloes.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] On very rare occasions, buffaloes and white rhinos will fight over territory; due to the rhino's strength and size advantage, the rhino typically wins and the buffalo can die from injuries sustained during the encounter.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] Rhinos live solitary lives, whereas buffalo (excluding solitary adult bulls) primarily live social lives and thus they do not usually recognize each other as threats.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] Hippopotamuses and buffalo also do not normally interact, but if the buffalo provokes the hippo or makes it feel threatened, a fight can break out, but this is also rare.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] The average-sized Nile crocodile typically attacks only old solitary animals and young calves, though they can kill healthy adults.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] Exceptionally large, old male crocodiles may become semi-habitual predators of buffaloes.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] The cheetah, leopard, African wild dog and spotted hyena are normally a threat only to newborn calves, though larger clans of hyenas have been recorded killing cows (mainly pregnant ones) and, on rare occasions, full-grown bulls.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] Large packs of wild dogs have been observed to hunt calves and sick adults.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] The African buffalo is susceptible to many diseases, including those shared with domestic cattle, such as bovine tuberculosis, corridor disease, and foot-and-mouth disease.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] As with many diseases, these problems remain dormant within a population as long as the health of the animals is good.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] These diseases do, however, restrict the legal movements of the animals and fencing infected areas from unaffected areas is enforced.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] Some wardens and game managers have managed to protect and breed "disease-free" herds which become very valuable because they can be transported.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] Most well-known are Lindsay Hunt's efforts to source uninfected animals from the Kruger National Park in South Africa.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] Some disease-free buffaloes in South Africa have been sold to breeders for close to US$130,000.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] The core of the herds is made up of related females, and their offspring, in an almost linear dominance hierarchy.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] The basic herds are surrounded by subherds of subordinate males, high-ranking males and females, and old or invalid animals.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] African buffaloes engage in several types of group behavior.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] Females appear to exhibit a sort of "voting behavior".
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] During resting time, the females stand up, shuffle around, and sit back down again.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] They sit in the direction they think they should move.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] After an hour of more shuffling, the females travel in the direction they decide.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] This decision is communal and not based on hierarchy or dominance.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] When chased by predators, a herd sticks close together and makes it hard for the predators to pick off one member.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] A buffalo herd responds to the distress call of a threatened member and tries to rescue it.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] A calf's distress call gets the attention of not only the mother, but also the herd.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] Buffaloes engage in mobbing behavior when fighting off predators.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] They have been recorded killing lions and chasing lions up trees and keeping them there for two hours, after the lions have killed a member of their group.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] In one videotaped instance, known as the *Battle at Kruger*, a calf survived an attack by both lions and a crocodile after intervention of the herd.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] Males have a linear dominance hierarchy based on age and size.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] Since a buffalo is safer when a herd is larger, dominant bulls may rely on subordinate bulls and sometimes tolerate their copulation.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] The young males keep their distance from the dominant bull, which is recognizable by the thickness of his horns.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] Adult bulls spar in play, dominance interactions, or actual fights.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] A bull approaches another, lowing, with his horns down, and waits for the other bull to do the same thing.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] When sparring, the bulls twist their horns from side to side.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] If the sparring is for play, the bull may rub his opponent's face and body during the sparring session.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] Actual fights are violent but rare and brief.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] Calves may also spar in play, but adult females rarely spar at all.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] During the dry season, males split from the herd and form bachelor groups.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] Two types of bachelor herds occur: ones made of males aged four to seven years and those of males 12 years or older.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] During the wet season, the younger bulls rejoin a herd to mate with the females.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] They stay with them throughout the season to protect the calves.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] Some older bulls cease to rejoin the herd, as they can no longer compete with the younger, more aggressive males.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] The old bachelors are called *dagga boy*s ("mud covered"), and are considered the most dangerous to humans.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] African buffaloes make various vocalizations.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] Many calls are lower-pitched versions of those emitted by domestic cattle.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] They emit low-pitched, two- to four-second calls intermittently at three- to six-second intervals to signal the herd to move.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] To signal to the herd to change direction, leaders emit "gritty", "creaking gate" sounds.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] When moving to drinking places, some individuals make long "maaa" calls up to 20 times a minute.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] When being aggressive, they make explosive grunts that may last long or turn into a rumbling growl.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] Cows produce croaking calls when looking for their calves.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] Calves make a similar call of a higher pitch when in distress.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] When threatened by predators, they make drawn-out "waaaa" calls.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] Dominant individuals make calls to announce their presence and location.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] A version of the same call, but more intense, is emitted as a warning to an encroaching inferior.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] When grazing, they make various sounds, such as brief bellows, grunts, honks, and croaks.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] Females reach sexual maturity at around five years of age while males are sexually matured at four to six.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] African buffaloes mate and give birth only during the rainy seasons.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] Birth peak takes place early in the season, while mating peaks later.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] A bull closely guards a cow that comes into heat, while keeping other bulls at bay.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] This is difficult, as cows are quite evasive and attract many males to the scene.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] By the time a cow is in full estrus, only the most dominant bull in the herd/subherd is there.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] Cows first calve at five years of age, after a gestation period of 11.5 months.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] Newborn calves remain hidden in vegetation for the first few weeks while being nursed occasionally by the mother before joining the main herd.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] Older calves are held in the centre of the herd for safety.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] The maternal bond between mother and calf lasts longer than in most bovids.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] That bonding ends when a new calf is born, and the mother then keeps her previous offspring at bay with horn jabs.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] Nevertheless, the yearling follows its mother for another year or so.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] Males leave their mothers when they are two years old and join the bachelor groups.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] Young calves, unusually for bovids, suckle from behind their mothers, pushing their heads between the mothers' legs.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] In the wild African buffaloes have an average lifespan of 11 years but they have been recorded to reach 22 years of age.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] In captivity they can live for a maximum of 29.5 years though they only live 16 years on average.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] The current status of the African buffalo is dependent on the animal's value to both trophy hunters and tourists, paving the way for conservation efforts through anti-poaching patrols, village crop damage payouts, and CAMPFIRE payback programs to local areas.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] The African buffalo is categorized as "Near Threatened" by the IUCN, with a decreasing population of 400,000 individuals.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] In the most recent and available census data at continental scale, the estimated total number of the three savanna-type African buffalo subspecies (*S. c. caffer*, *S. c. brachyceros* and *S. c. aequinoctialis*) combined is 513,000 individuals.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] In the past, numbers of African buffaloes suffered their most severe collapse during the great rinderpest epidemic of the 1890s, which, coupled with pleuro-pneumonia, caused mortalities as high as 95% among both livestock and wild ungulates.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] Being a member of the Big Five game group, a term used to describe the five most dangerous animals to hunt, the Cape buffalo is a sought-after trophy, with some hunters paying over $10,000 for the opportunity to hunt one.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] The larger bulls are targeted for their trophy value, although in some areas, buffaloes are still hunted for meat.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] One of the Big Five game, the African buffalo has been nicknamed "the Black Death" or "the widowmaker" due to it being widely regarded as a very dangerous animal.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] African buffaloes are notorious amongst big-game hunters in particular as very dangerous animals, with wounded animals reported to ambush and attack the hunters.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] African buffaloes are sometimes reported to kill more people in Africa than any other animal, although the same claim is also made of hippopotamuses and crocodiles.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] These numbers may be somewhat overestimated; for example, in Mozambique, attacks on humans, especially fatal ones, were much less frequent than those by either hippos or, especially, Nile crocodiles.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] Conversely, in Uganda, large herbivores were found to both attack more people on average than either lions or leopards, and to inflict a higher rate of fatalities during those attacks (almost 50%) than the felids.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] However, both hippos and elephants may still kill more people per annum than buffaloes.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] In August 2025, Asher Watkins, a 52‑year‑old American rancher and trophy hunter, was killed by a Cape buffalo he was tracking during a safari in Limpopo Province, South Africa.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] Reportedly, the buffalo charged Watkins at approximately 35 mph (56 km/h), resulting in fatal injuries.
[src:african-buffalo/african-buffalo] The Cape buffalo has been bred with the Indian water buffalo to produce the Jafarabadi buffalo breed.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Both species are at risk of extinction according to the IUCN Red List; as of 2021, the bush elephant is considered endangered while the forest elephant is considered critically endangered.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] They are threatened by habitat loss and fragmentation, along with poaching for the illegal ivory trade in several range countries.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] The name *Loxodonta* comes from the Ancient Greek words λοξός (*loxós,*"slanting", "crosswise") and ὀδούς (*odoús*, "tooth"), referring to the lozenge-shaped enamel of the molar teeth, which differs significantly from the rounded shape of the Asian elephant's molar enamel.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] The first scientific description of the African elephant was written in 1797 by Johann Friedrich Blumenbach, who proposed the scientific name *Elephas africanus*.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] *Loxodonte* was proposed as a generic name for the African elephant by Frédéric Cuvier in 1825.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] An anonymous author used the Latinized spelling *Loxodonta* in 1827.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] This author was recognized as authority by the International Code of Zoological Nomenclature in 1999.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] In 1907, Richard Lydekker proposed six African elephant subspecies based on the different sizes and shapes of their ears.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] They are all considered synonymous with the African bush elephant.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] A third species, the West African elephant, has also been proposed but needs confirmation.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] It is thought that this lineage has been isolated from the others for 2.4 million years.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Relationships of living and extinct elephants based on DNA, after Palkopoulou et al.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] The oldest species of *Loxodonta* known is *Loxodonta cookei,* with remains of the species known from around 7–5 million years ago, from remains found in Chad, Kenya, Uganda, and South Africa.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Analysis of nuclear DNA sequences indicates that the genetic divergence between African bush and forest elephants dates 2.6 – 5.6 million years ago.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] The African forest elephant was found to have a high degree of genetic diversity, likely reflecting periodic fragmentation of their habitat during the changes in the Pleistocene.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Gene flow between the two African elephant species was examined at 21 locations.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] The analysis revealed that several African bush elephants carried mitochondrial DNA of African forest elephants, indicating they hybridised in the savanna-forest transition zone in ancient times.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] However, despite the hybridisation at the contact zone between the two species, there appears to have been little effective gene flow between the two species since their initial split.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] DNA from the European straight-tusked elephant (*Palaeoloxodon antiquus*) indicates that the extinct elephant genus *Palaeoloxodon* is more closely related to African elephants than to Asian elephants or mammoths.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Analysis of Chinese *Palaeoloxodon* mitogenomes suggests that this forest elephant ancestry was widely shared among *Palaeoloxodon* species.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] African elephants have grey folded skin up to 30 mm (1.2 in) thick that is covered with sparse, bristled dark-brown to black hair.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Short tactile hair grows on the trunk, which has two finger-like processes at the tip, whereas Asian elephants only have one.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Their large ears help to reduce body heat.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Flapping them creates air currents and exposes the ears' inner sides where large blood vessels increase heat loss during hot weather.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] The trunk is a prehensile elongation of its upper lip and nose.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] This highly sensitive organ is innervated primarily by the trigeminal nerve, and is thought to be manipulated by about 40,000–60,000 muscles.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Because of this muscular structure, the trunk is so strong that elephants can use it to lift about 3% of their own body weight.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] They use it for smelling, touching, feeding, drinking, dusting, producing sounds, loading, defending and attacking.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Elephants sometimes swim underwater and use their trunks as snorkels.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Both male and female African elephants have tusks that grow from deciduous teeth called tushes, which are replaced by tusks when calves are about one year old.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Tusks are composed of dentin, which forms small diamond-shaped structures in the tusk's center that become larger at its periphery.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Tusks are primarily used to dig for roots and strip the bark from trees for food, for fighting each other during the mating season, and for defending themselves against predators.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] The tusks weigh from 23 to 45 kg (51–99 lb) and can be from 1.5 to 2.4 m (5–8 ft) long.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] They are curved forward and continue to grow throughout the elephant's lifetime.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Elephants have four molars; each weighs about 5 kg (11 lb) and measures about 30 cm (12 in) long.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] As the front pair wears down and drops out in pieces, the back pair moves forward, and two new molars emerge in the back of the mouth.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Elephants replace their teeth four to six times in their lifetimes.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] At around 40 to 60 years of age, the elephant loses the last of its molars and will likely die of starvation which is a common cause of death.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] African elephants have 24 teeth in total, six on each quadrant of the jaw.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] The enamel plates of the molars are fewer in number than in Asian elephants.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] The enamel of the molar teeth wears into a distinctive lozenge/loxodont (**<>**) shape characteristic to all members of the genus *Loxodonta*.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] While some extinct species of *Loxodonta* retained permanent premolar teeth, these have been lost in both living species.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] The African bush elephant is the largest terrestrial animal.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] The largest recorded bull stood 3.96 m (13.0 ft) at the shoulder and is estimated to have weighed 10.4 t (10.2 long tons; 11.5 short tons).
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Its back is concave-shaped, while the back of the African forest elephant is nearly straight.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] The African forest elephant is considerably smaller.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Fully grown African forest elephant males in optimal conditions where individuals are capable of reaching full growth potential are estimated to be on average 2.09–2.31 m (6.9–7.6 ft) tall and 1.7–2.3 t (1.7–2.3 long tons; 1.9–2.5 short tons) in weight.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] African elephants are distributed in Sub-Saharan Africa, where they inhabit Sahelian scrubland and arid regions, tropical rainforests, mopane and miombo woodlands.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] African forest elephant populations occur only in Central and West Africa.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Both African elephant species live in family units comprising several adult cows, their daughters and their subadult sons.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Each family unit is led by an older cow known as the matriarch.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] African forest elephant groups are less cohesive than African bush elephant groups, probably due to the lack of natural predators.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] When separate family units bond, they form kinship or bond groups.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] After puberty, male elephants tend to form close alliances with other males.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] While females are the most active members of African elephant groups, both male and female elephants are capable of distinguishing between hundreds of different low-frequency infrasonic calls to communicate with and identify each other.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Elephants use some vocalisations that are beyond the hearing range of humans, to communicate across large distances.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Elephant mating rituals include the gentle entwining of trunks.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Bulls were believed to be solitary animals, becoming independent once reaching maturity.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] New research suggests that bulls maintain ecological knowledge for the herd, facilitating survival when searching for food and water, which also benefits the young bulls who associate with them.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Bulls only return to the herd to breed or to socialize; they do not provide parental care to their offspring or raise them, but rather play a fatherly role in general to younger bulls to show dominance.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] African elephants are not strictly territorial but they display various types of patterns of space use which are influenced by social structure, seasonal and climate variation, and resource availability.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Additional factors such as social dominance and environmental factors like rainfall and vegetation productivity also influences spatial segregation among groups within the same region.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] African elephants displays complex patterns of aggression accompanied with dominance, especially within adult males.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Musth is a term which refers to physiological state where male African elephants exhibit massive surges of testosterone, heightened sexual activity, and increased aggression and is observed during male - male competition.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] During the period where male African elephant undergo musth, they display characteristic behavior which includes temporal gland secretion, urine dribbling, and certain postures which explains their condition to other individuals.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] By performing these behaviors, male African elephants reduces the need for physical confrontation by communicating dominance status.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] However, in cases where these type of communication fails, aggressive encounters including tusking and pushing may occur when competing for receptive females.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] The dominance hierarchy within a herd of elephants are largely influenced and based on age, size, and musth status with older males typically outcompeting younger or non-musth individuals.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] African elephants are generalist herbivores and consume a wide variety of leaves, grasses, bark, and fruits, but woody vegetation in dry seasons.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] While feeding, they pluck leaves and tear at branches using tusks, which can cause enormous damage to foliage.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Fermentation of the food takes place in the hindgut, enabling large food intakes.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] The large size and hindgut of the African elephant also allows for the digestion of various plant parts, including fibrous stems, bark and roots.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] African elephants aid in germination of seeds thanks to their large stomachs; as they are able to cover a large area within one day, they spread seeds from different trees rapidly.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] The elephants graze on the trees and consume seeds from them, and then, with the seed passing through the gastrointestinal tract and then secreted out, the seeds are fertilized and ready to grow.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] The germination via elephants prevents plant competition and removes the requirement for some seeds to be wind-blown to grow, or the process of random germination.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] The diversity of plants and trees that can grow through this process also increases because the dung piles can contain upwards of 10 different tree species, with some containing traces of 50 trees and above.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] African elephants are highly intelligent.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] They have a very large and highly convoluted neocortex, a trait they share with humans and other apes, as well as some dolphin species.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] They are among the world's most intelligent species.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] With a mass of just over 5 kg (11 lb), the elephant brain is larger than that of any other terrestrial animal.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] The elephant's brain is similar to a human brain in terms of structure and complexity; the elephant's cortex has as many neurons as that of a human brain, suggesting convergent evolution.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Elephants exhibit a wide variety of behaviours, including those associated with grief, learning, mimicry, art, play, a sense of humor, altruism, use of tools, compassion, cooperation, self-awareness, memory and possibly language.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] All of these behaviors point to a highly intelligent species that is thought to be equal to cetaceans and primates.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] The African elephant's cognitive complexity includes behaviors indicative of empathy, problem-solving, and cooperative group behaviors.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] These traits underscore the evolutionary convergence of intelligence across species, similar to that seen in primates and cetaceans.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] African elephants are at their most fertile between the ages of 25 and 45 years.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Calves are normally born after a gestation period of 22 months.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] The calves are cared for by their mother and other young females in the group, known as allomothering.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Female African elephants are able to start reproducing at around 10 to 12 years of age.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Post sexual maturity, males begin to experience musth, a physical and behavioral condition that is characterized by elevated testosterone, aggression and more sexual activity.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Musth also serves a purpose of calling attention to the females that they are of good quality, and it cannot be mimicked as certain calls or noises may be.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Males sire few offspring in periods when they are not in musth.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] During the middle of estrus, female elephants look for males in musth to guard them.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] The females will yell, in a loud, low way to attract males from far away.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Male elephants can also smell the hormones of a female ready for breeding.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] This leads males to compete with each other to mate, which results in the females mating with older, healthier males.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Females choose to a point who they mate with, since they are the ones who try to get males to compete to guard them.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] However, females are not guarded in the early and late stages of estrus, which may permit mating by younger males not in musth.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Males over the age of 25 compete strongly for females in estrus, and are more successful the larger and more aggressive they are.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Bigger males tend to sire bigger offspring.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Wild males begin breeding in their thirties when they are at a size and weight that is competitive with other adult males.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Male reproductive success is maximal in mid-adulthood and then begins to decline.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] However, this can depend on the ranking of the male within their group, as higher-ranking males maintain a higher rate of reproduction.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Most observed matings are by males in musth over 35 years of age.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Both species are threatened by habitat loss and fragmentation.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Poaching for the illegal ivory trade is a threat in several range countries as well.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] The African bush elephant is listed as Endangered and the African forest elephant as Critically Endangered on the respective IUCN Red Lists.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Based on vegetation types that provide suitable habitat for African elephants, it was estimated that in the early 19th century a maximum of 26,913,000 African elephants might have been present from the Sahel in the north to the Highveld in the south.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Decrease of suitable habitat was the major cause for the decline of elephant populations until the 1950s.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Hunting African elephants for the ivory trade accelerated the decline from the 1970s onwards.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] The carrying capacity of remaining suitable habitats was estimated at 8,985,000 elephants at most by 1987.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] In the 1970s and 1980s, the price of ivory rose, and poaching for ivory increased, particularly in Central African range countries where access to elephant habitats was facilitated by logging and petroleum mining industries.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Between 1976 and 1980, about 830 t (820 long tons; 910 short tons) raw ivory was exported from Africa to Hong Kong and Japan, equivalent to tusks of about 222,000 African elephants.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] The first continental elephant census was carried out in 1976.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] At the time, 1.34 million elephants were estimated to range over 7,300,000 km2 (2,800,000 sq mi).
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] In the 1980s, it was difficult to carry out systematic surveys in several East African range countries due to civil wars.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] In 1987, it was estimated that the African elephant population had declined to 760,000 individuals.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] In 1989, only 608,000 African elephants were estimated to have survived.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] In 1989, the Kenyan Wildlife Service burned a stockpile of tusks in protest against the ivory trade.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] When the international ivory trade reopened in 2006, the demand and price for ivory increased in Asia.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] In Chad's Zakouma National Park, more than 3,200 elephants were killed between 2005 and 2010.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] The park did not have sufficient guards to combat poaching and their weapons were outdated.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Well organized networks facilitated smuggling the ivory through Sudan.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] The government of Tanzania estimated that more than 85,000 elephants were lost to poaching in Tanzania between 2009 and 2014, representing a 60% loss.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] In 2012, a large upsurge in ivory poaching was reported, with about 70% of the product flowing to China.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] China was the biggest market for poached ivory but announced that it would phase out the legal domestic manufacture and sale of ivory products in May 2015.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Conflicts between elephants and a growing human population are a major issue in elephant conservation.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Human encroachment into natural areas where bush elephants occur or their increasing presence in adjacent areas has spurred research into methods of safely driving groups of elephants away from humans.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Playback of the recorded sounds of angry Western honey bees has been found to be remarkably effective at prompting elephants to flee an area.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Farmers have tried scaring elephants away by more aggressive means such as fire or the use of chili peppers along fences to protect their crops.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] The main threats to African elephants are habitat loss and poaching, in addition to these main, most concerning threats, more recent threats emerged which includes human-made barriers and landscape modification which significantly affect and limits African elephant movement and distribution.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Construction of fences, roads, artificial water points, and agricultural lands have reported severe impact in altering natural movement patterns, fragmenting habitats, and limiting access to seasonal resources.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] In 1986, the African Elephant Database was initiated with the aim to monitor the status of African elephant populations.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] This database includes results from aerial surveys, dung counts, interviews with local people and data on poaching.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] In 1989, the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species of Wild Fauna and Flora listed the African elephant on CITES Appendix I.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] This listing banned international trade of African elephants and their body parts by countries that signed the CITES agreement.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Hunting elephants is banned in the Central African Republic, Democratic Republic of Congo, Gabon, Côte d'Ivoire, and Senegal.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] After the ban came into force in 1990, retail sales of ivory carvings in South Africa have plummeted by more than 95% within 10 years.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] As a result of the trade ban, African elephant populations recovered in Southern African range countries.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] The African Elephant Specialist Group has set up a *Human-Elephant Conflict Task Force* with the aim to develop conflict mitigation strategies.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] In 2005, the West African Elephant Memorandum of Understanding was signed by 12 West African countries.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] The Convention on the Conservation of Migratory Species of Wild Animals provided financial support for four years to implement the West African Elephant Conservation Strategy, which forms the central component of this intergovernmental treaty.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] In 2019, the export of wild African elephants to zoos around the world was banned, with an exception added by the EU to allow export in "exceptional cases where … it is considered that a transfer to ex-situ locations will provide demonstrable in-situ conservation benefits for African elephants".
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Previously, export had been allowed in Southern Africa with Zimbabwe capturing and exporting more than 100 baby elephants to Chinese zoos since 2012.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] It was found that elephant conservation does not pose a trade-off with climate change mitigation.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Although animals typically cause a reduction of woody biomass and therewith above-ground carbon, they foster soil carbon sequestration.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Recent conservation approaches for African elephants are more focused on territorial-level management and the maintenance of ecological connectivity between fragmented areas where artificial causes are the main factor influencing African elephant population.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] By interpreting on migration corridors and by sustaining connection between protected areas, it would support natural movement patterns and balanced access to seasonal resources.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Conservation strategies will include efforts to weaken the impacts of human infrastructure such as removal of fences and improved land use planning which would propose to reduce habitat fragmentation and human elephant conflict.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Additional factors which would reinforce African elephant conservation includes coordinated international management as elephant territories are distributed broadly across the Africa plains and safari regions, and the integration of local communities into conservation planning.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Many African cultures revere the elephant as a symbol of strength and power.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] It is also praised for its size, longevity, stamina, mental faculties, cooperative spirit, and loyalty.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Its religious importance is mostly totemic.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] Many societies believed that their chiefs would be reincarnated as elephants.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] In the 10th century, the people of Igbo-Ukwu in Nigeria buried their leaders with elephant tusks.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] South Africa uses elephant tusks in their coat of arms to represent wisdom, strength, moderation and eternity.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] In the western African Kingdom of Dahomey (now Benin), the elephant was associated with the 19th century rulers of the Fon people, Guezo and his son Glele.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] The coat of arms of the Central African Republic features the head of an elephant in the upper left quadrant of the shield.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] The version of the coat of arms of Guinea used from 1958 to 1984 featured a golden elephant in the centre of the shield.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] The coat of arms of Ivory Coast features the head of an elephant as the focal point of the emblem.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] The coat of arms of the Republic of the Congo has two elephants supporting the shield.
[src:african-buffalo/african-elephant] The coat of arms of Eswatini has an elephant and a lion supporting the shield.
[src:african-buffalo/african-forest-buffalo] The **African forest buffalo** (***Syncerus caffer nanus***), also known as the **dwarf buffalo**, **red buffalo**, **Congo buffalo** or **bush-cow**, is the smallest subspecies of the African buffalo.
[src:african-buffalo/african-forest-buffalo] It is related to the Cape buffalo (*Syncerus caffer caffer*), the Sudan buffalo (*Syncerus caffer brachyceros*), and the Nile buffalo (*Syncerus caffer aequinoctialis*).
[src:african-buffalo/african-forest-buffalo] However, it is the only subspecies that occurs mainly in the rainforests of Central Africa and Western Africa, with an annual rainfall around 1,500 mm (59 in).
[src:african-buffalo/african-forest-buffalo] It has been proposed to represent a distinct species, ***Syncerus nanus***.
[src:african-buffalo/african-forest-buffalo] The African forest buffalo is a small subspecies of the African buffalo.
[src:african-buffalo/african-forest-buffalo] Cape buffaloes weigh 425 to 870 kg (937 to 1,918 lb), whereas African forest buffaloes are much lighter, weighing in at 250 to 320 kg (550–705 lbs).
[src:african-buffalo/african-forest-buffalo] Weight is not the only differentiation, however; this subspecies has a reddish-brown hide that is darker in the facial area.
[src:african-buffalo/african-forest-buffalo] The shape and size of the horns distinguish African forest buffalo from the other subspecies.
[src:african-buffalo/african-forest-buffalo] African forest buffalo have much smaller horns than their savanna counterparts the Cape, Sudan and Nile buffalo.
[src:african-buffalo/african-forest-buffalo] Cape buffalo horns often grow and fuse together, but African forest buffalo horns rarely fuse.
[src:african-buffalo/african-forest-buffalo] African forest buffalo live in the rainforests of West and Central Africa; however, their home ranges typically consist of a combination of marshes, grassy savannas and the wet African rainforests.
[src:african-buffalo/african-forest-buffalo] Savannas are the area where the buffalo graze, while the marshes serve as wallows and help the animals handle insects.
[src:african-buffalo/african-forest-buffalo] African forest buffalo are very rarely observed in the unbroken canopy of the forests.
[src:african-buffalo/african-forest-buffalo] They instead spend most of their time in clearings, grazing on grasses and sedges.
[src:african-buffalo/african-forest-buffalo] Consequently, their diet is primarily made up of grasses and other plants that grow in clearings and savannas.
[src:african-buffalo/african-forest-buffalo] The mixture of habitats is essential for the African forest buffalo.
[src:african-buffalo/african-forest-buffalo] Expansion and encroachment of the rainforest on the surrounding savannas and openings are major difficulties of maintaining the ecosystem.
[src:african-buffalo/african-forest-buffalo] African forest buffalo enjoy old logging roads and tracks, where the forest is thinner and grass and other foods can grow.
[src:african-buffalo/african-forest-buffalo] In these areas, African forest buffalo depend on the grass that is able to develop as a result of the areas that have been previously clear-cut.
[src:african-buffalo/african-forest-buffalo] In some areas park management staff burn off the savannas on a regular basis to keep the rainforest from growing onto the savannas and changing the ecosystem of the area.
[src:african-buffalo/african-forest-buffalo] Large home ranges can be associated with less-productive habitats; however, a larger area of open grassland has been observed to have a positive relationship with herd size.
[src:african-buffalo/african-forest-buffalo] Home ranges remain remarkably constant and stable year after year.
[src:african-buffalo/african-forest-buffalo] The only documentation of the actual home range boundaries of these animals is relatively recent, so only time will tell how these boundaries remain over large lengths of time; however, studies have shown almost no movement in range boundaries from one year to the next.
[src:african-buffalo/african-forest-buffalo] Although the area included in a home range is relatively constant over time, the preferences in regard to what part of the range is most used shift with the seasons.
[src:african-buffalo/african-forest-buffalo] From March until August, African forest buffalo spend most of their time in the forest, while from September through February, they favor the savannas and marshes.
[src:african-buffalo/african-forest-buffalo] African forest buffalo arrange themselves into herds, which help in defense against predators; however, they are not immune to assault.
[src:african-buffalo/african-forest-buffalo] Among predators, the African leopard is the most common, but is generally only a threat to young buffaloes and will feast on them only when they have the opportunity.
[src:african-buffalo/african-forest-buffalo] The Nile crocodile is the only predator that is capable of killing an adult buffalo.
[src:african-buffalo/african-forest-buffalo] African forest buffalo have relatively small herds compared to the well-studied Cape buffalo.
[src:african-buffalo/african-forest-buffalo] Cape buffalo can have herds of over 1,000 members; however, African forest buffalo stay in much smaller groups—as small as three and rarely over 30.
[src:african-buffalo/african-forest-buffalo] If African forest buffalo are in a large group, they spend more time grazing, since there is less need to devote time to alert behavior.
[src:african-buffalo/african-forest-buffalo] A herd of African forest buffalo typically consists of one or occasionally two bulls and a harem of adult females, juveniles and young calves.
[src:african-buffalo/african-forest-buffalo] Unlike Cape buffalo bulls, African forest buffalo bulls remain with the herd continually, year round.
[src:african-buffalo/african-forest-buffalo] On the other hand, Cape buffalo bulls stay in bachelor herds until the wet season, when young bulls join the females, mate, help protect the young calves and then leave.
[src:african-buffalo/african-forest-buffalo] Animals usually remain in the same herd for their entire lives.
[src:african-buffalo/african-forest-buffalo] Herd-switching in cows has been observed; however, this is not a common occurrence.
[src:african-buffalo/african-forest-buffalo] Herds can split into two groups for a short period of time before merging back together.
[src:african-buffalo/african-forest-buffalo] African forest buffalo are relatively unaffected by seasonal cycles.
[src:african-buffalo/african-forest-buffalo] However, in the wet season, herds are more spread out in the forest and these animals tend to use resting places based on sand during the wet season, but use dirt and leaves during the dry season.
[src:african-buffalo/african-forest-buffalo] Moreover, in open habitats such as clearings, herds are more aggregated when resting and are more rounded in shape than herds in forest habitats during the wet season.
